An Isotopic Perspective into the Magmatic Evolution and Architecture of the Rift Zones of Kīlauea Volcano

, , , ,
Journal of Petrology, Volume 59, Issue 12, December 2018, Pages 2311–2352, https://doi.org/10.1093/petrology/egy098
Published:
30 October 2018
Article history
  • PDF
  • Split View
  • Cite
  • Permissions Icon Permissions
  • Share Icon Share

Abstract

The basic model for the plumbing system of Kīlauea Volcano states that (1) compositionally distinct batches of primitive mantle-derived magma ascend through a primary conduit to the volcano’s summit magma storage reservoir and (2) this olivine-controlled magma is mixed and stored prior to eruption at the summit or lateral intrusion into the East Rift Zone (ERZ) or Southwest Rift Zone (SWRZ) for further storage, mixing, differentiation and/or eruption. In detail, however, the magmatic architecture of Kīlauea’s rift zones and their connection to the summit reservoir and the deeper source(s) of melt from the Hawaiian mantle plume, is more complicated. Here we use the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions of historical Kīlauea summit and rift lavas, from 1959 to the recent eruptions at Puʻu ʻŌʻō and Halemaʻumaʻu, to test models for the volcano’s rift zones and decipher their magmatic evolution. These samples (including a 1919 summit lava) record a rapid and systematic variation in 206Pb/204Pb (18·39 to 18·66), 87Sr/86Sr (0·70347 to 0·70364), and εNd (+5·9 to +6·5) that derives from changes in the composition of the parental magma delivered to the volcano. Assimilation of the Pacific oceanic crust and/or the Hawaiian volcanic edifice does not significantly modify the isotopic composition of mantle-derived Kīlauea magmas. Many contemporaneous summit and rift lavas display small, but statistically significant, differences in 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr that are used to (1) identify magma batches from the mantle and (2) track their movement though the ERZ and/or SWRZ. A series of intrusions from the summit reservoir to the ERZ in the 1960s left behind a large amount of magma that became a prominent mixing component in subsequent rift lavas. Variations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of lavas from the Mauna Ulu rift eruption (1969–1974) are mostly related to mixing within the ERZ between stored 1960s-era magma and at least two new mantle-derived magmas. Lavas from several upper ERZ (UERZ) eruptions in the 1960s and 1970s (including the August 1968 eruption, the Mauna Ulu eruption, and additionally, the eccentric December 1974 eruption near the volcano’s summit) may each contain at least one component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. The early differentiated lavas from the Puʻu ʻŌʻō rift eruption (1983–2018) were stored in the middle ERZ (MERZ) since the 1960s. This stored magma was rapidly flushed from the ERZ by olivine-controlled 1982-era summit magma, the last of which erupted at Puʻu ʻŌʻō by ∼1990. Thereafter, Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas display (1) short-term fluctuations in 206Pb/204Pb on a time scale of <10 years and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr from ∼0·70359 to a maximum of ∼0·70364 between ∼2000 and 2003, and a slight decrease thereafter. These mantle-derived isotopic variations were efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface because Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas were poorly buffered by the small volume of magma within the summit reservoir and UERZ to MERZ (∼0·2 km3, as inferred from a magma mixing trend). An increase in the maximum duration of pre-eruptive magma storage from the UERZ (<7 yr) to the MERZ (<19 yr) and, on average, the more differenatiated nature of downrift lavas is likely controlled by a decrease in the long-term average rate of magma supply to the more distal portions of the ERZ. Our results support recent models for Kīlauea’s plumbing system: (1) the summit reservoir comprises two magma bodies; (2) the ERZ is connected to the ∼2–4 km deep summit magma body beneath the southern rim of the caldera; (3) the volcanic SWRZ is connected to the < 2 km deep summit magma body beneath the eastern rim of Halemaʻumaʻu.

Original Papers

INTRODUCTION

The spatial and temporal variations in the composition of lava from active volcanoes provide a detailed view of the number, size, and location of their underlying magma bodies, and the residence time of magma within them (e.g. Cortini & Scandone, 1982; Albarède, 1993; Vlastélic et al., 2007, 2009). Kīlauea Volcano, located on the Island of Hawai’i (Fig. 1), displays systematic variations in lava chemistry on time scales of years to centuries (Fig. 2) due to mantle source heterogeneity and variations in the melting process (e.g. Wright & Tilling, 1980; Hofmann et al., 1984; Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013). These mantle-derived changes in the composition of the parental melt delivered to the volcano are subsequently modulated by the transport, mixing, and storage of magma beneath Kīlauea’s summit (e.g. Wright, 1971; Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999b; Garcia et al., 2003; Pietruszka et al., 2015) and within its two rift zones (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Garcia et al., 1989, 1992; Thornber et al., 2015). The interplay of these mantle vs crustal processes at Kīlauea is poorly understood. For example, at least nine compositionally distinct batches of mantle-derived magma have been inferred for eruptions at the summit of Kīlauea from 1952 to 1982, based on the major element abundances of the lavas (e.g. Helz et al., 2014; Wright & Klein, 2014). However, modeling of the Pb isotope ratios of summit lavas erupted during the late 20th century suggests that only two magma batches are needed (one from 1959 to 1968 and the other from 1971 to 1982), each with a narrow range in 206Pb/204Pb (Pietruszka et al., 2015). The remaining variation in 206Pb/204Pb may be attributed to magma mixing and a short magma residence time (∼2–3 years) within the volcano’s summit magma storage reservoir (Fig. 3).

Until May 2018, an active lava lake within Halemaʻumaʻu was supplied from the HMM body (itself connected to the SC body), and a dike transported magma from the SC body to Puʻu ʻŌʻō on the ERZ (Poland et al., 2014; Thornber et al., 2015). Three additional magma pathways (dashed grey areas) that were not recently active are from Poland et al. (2014): the volcanic SWRZ, the seismic SWRZ, and the Halemaʻumaʻu–Kīlauea Iki Trend (HKIT). The sizes of the two summit magma bodies and the prominent volcanic shields, cones, and craters on the rift zones are exaggerated for clarity. The current state of Kīlauea’s magmatic plumbing system is unknown.

Lavas from the Puʻu ʻŌʻō rift eruption (1983–2018) show two cycles in their K2O/TiO2 ratios from 1996 to 2001 (superimposed on a longer-term decreasing trend) that seem to correlate with the inflation and deflation of the volcano’s summit region (Thornber, 2003). This behavior was interpreted to result from mixing between a compositionally homogeneous Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type mantle-derived input magma (with a low K2O/TiO2 ratio) and variable, decreasing amounts of stored 1982-era magma (with a high K2O/TiO2 ratio) from the summit reservoir (Thornber, 2003; Thornber et al., 2015). In contrast, Greene et al. (2013) observed small fluctuations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/206Pb ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas on a time scale of <10 years (1986 to 2010) that were interpreted to result directly from the melting of filament-shaped compositional heterogeneities (only ∼1–3 km in diameter) within the Hawaiian mantle plume. These rapid, mantle-derived changes in Pb isotopic composition might be efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface if the parental magmas for the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption partially bypassed the volcano’s summit reservoir, and avoided its buffering effects (e.g. Garcia et al., 1996). In this study, we use the compositional variations of Kīlauea lavas in space and time to better resolve this type of ‘top down’ vs ‘bottom up’ debate (e.g. Thornber, 2003) and investigate the magmatic processes that operate within the plumbing system of this frequently active basaltic volcano.

The architecture of Kīlauea’s magmatic plumbing system (Fig. 3) is relatively well understood (e.g. Eaton & Murata, 1960; Tilling & Dvorak, 1993). Primitive magma from the mantle ascends through a primary conduit to Kīlauea’s summit reservoir (e.g. Ryan et al., 1981; Klein et al., 1987; Ryan, 1988), which comprises: (1) a ∼2–4 km deep body beneath the southern rim of the volcano’s caldera, called the ‘South Caldera’ (SC) magma body; and (2) a < 2 km deep body beneath the eastern rim of Halemaʻumaʻu (HMM) pit crater, called the HMM magma body (e.g. Fiske & Kinoshita, 1969; Battaglia et al., 2003; Cervelli & Miklius, 2003; Johnson et al., 2010; Baker & Amelung, 2012; Poland et al., 2014; Anderson et al., 2015). The presence of these two magma bodies beneath Kīlauea’s summit, possibly holding only ∼0·1–0·3 km3 of magma that can readily undergo mixing, is supported by the temporal and spatial variations in the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Magma within the summit reservoir (olivine controlled with >7 wt % MgO since 1959; Wright, 1971; Garcia et al., 2003) is mixed and stored prior to eruption at the summit or lateral intrusion into the East Rift Zone (ERZ) or Southwest Rift Zone (SWRZ) of the volcano (Fig. 4) for further storage, mixing, differentiation and/or eruption (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Garcia et al., 1989, 1992; Thornber et al., 2003).

The basic model for Kīlauea’s plumbing system states that all mantle-derived magma is first delivered from the primary conduit to the summit reservoir before intruding the rift zones via shallow dikes at depths of ∼4 km or less (e.g. Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Poland et al., 2014). This idea is consistent with the petrologic monitoring of lavas from the last three decades of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō ERZ eruption, and since 2008, the compositional similarity between Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas and contemporaneous tephra glasses from the recent lava lake within Halemaʻumaʻu (Pietruszka et al., 2015; Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015). In detail, however, the magmatic architecture of Kīlauea’s rift zones, and their connection to the summit reservoir and the deeper source(s) of melt from the Hawaiian plume, is more complicated. For example, each of the rift zones may consist of two distinct magma pathways (Fig. 3) that radiate from the summit reservoir at different depths (Poland et al., 2014): (1) the ‘volcanic SWRZ’ and the ‘Halemaʻumaʻu-Kīlauea Iki Trend’ (HKIT) are < 2 km deep and fed directly from the HMM magma body; and (2) the classic ERZ (which likely supplied magma to Puʻu ʻŌʻō) and the ‘seismic SWRZ’ are ∼2–4 km deep and fed directly from the SC magma body. Furthermore, studies of ground deformation (e.g. Delaney et al., 1990) and seismicity (e.g. Ryan et al., 1981; Ryan, 1988) suggest that deeper intrusions of magma (down to a depth of ∼9–10 km) may (at times) allow primitive mantle-derived magma to bypass the summit reservoir on its way to the rift zones. This hypothesis is controversial (e.g. Poland et al., 2014), but it would explain: (1) the presence of two olivine populations, possibly related to magma transport through the ERZ via two different routes, in lavas from the 1969–1974 Mauna Ulu ERZ eruption (Vinet & Higgins, 2010); (2) a wide range in the depth of crystallization (∼1–16 km) for olivine crystals (and their CO2-rich melt inclusions) from the 1960 ERZ eruption (Tuohy et al., 2016); (3) the eruption of new magma batches, identified from the major element abundances of the lavas, along the ERZ (as components in hybrid magmas) prior to their eruption at the summit (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980; Wright & Helz, 1996); and (4) seismic evidence for a deep (∼8–11 km) magma body beneath the ERZ (near Mauna Ulu) at the base of the volcanic edifice (Lin et al., 2014).

We present high-precision measurements of the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios, and major and trace element abundances of Kīlauea rift zone lavas from 1961 to 2012. These samples represent all of the SWRZ and ERZ eruptions from September 1961 to November 1979 (only the poorly documented March 1980 ERZ eruption is excluded). Published data for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013; Pietruszka et al., 2015), and new analyses of samples from 2006 to 2012, are used to extend this time series. In addition, the Sr and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea summit lavas from 1959 to 2010 (previously analysed only for Pb isotope ratios by Pietruszka et al. (2015)) are presented. Our approach, based on a detailed comparison of the isotopic composition of contemporaneous rift and summit lavas, is analogous to the studies of Wright (1971) and Wright & Fiske (1971), which used the major element abundances of Kīlauea lavas to identify magma batches from the mantle and track them through the summit reservoir and rift zones of the volcano. The major goals of this study are to: (1) establish the petrogenetic relationship between lavas from historical Kīlauea summit and rift eruptions (Table 1), based mostly on their Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions; (2) quantify the storage time of magma within the rift zones prior to each eruption (defined as the time elapsed since the emplacement of a given batch of summit-derived magma); (3) identify the components involved in magma mixing (if important) for each rift eruption; and (4) relate these storage times and mixing components to the architecture and evolution of the volcano’s magmatic plumbing system, with a focus on the rift zones.

ANALYTICAL METHODS

Thirty-two lavas from historical Kīlauea rift eruptions, summarized in Supplementary DataTable S1 (supplementary data are available for downloading at http://www.petrology.oxfordjournals.org) were analysed for major and trace element abundances by X-ray fluorescence spectrometry (XRF) at the University of Massachusetts, as described in the Supplementary Data. The XRF results (Supplementary DataTable S2) were used to select a representative subset of 27 samples of glass or rock chips from rift eruptions between September 1961 and November 1979 for isotopic analyses. In addition, 16 Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 2006 to 2012 and 29 historical Kīlauea summit lavas from 1959 to 2010 were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios [Pb isotopic data for these samples were reported in Greene et al. (2013) and Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. The Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions of the rift (Table 2) and summit (Table 3) samples were measured by: (1) multiple-collector inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (MC-ICP-MS) at San Diego State University (SDSU) for Pb (by high-precision ‘Tl doping’) and Nd (Nu Plasma HR or Nu Plasma 1700); and (2) thermal ionization mass spectrometry (TIMS) at SDSU (VG Sector 54) or the Southwest Isotope Research Laboratories (SWIRL) of the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) in Denver (Thermo Triton) for Sr. The methods for the isotopic analyses were previously described by Marske et al. (2007), except for the Sr isotopic measurements at the USGS SWIRL (see the Supplementary Data for additional details).

The USGS sample names for three of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō samples are KE58-2869 (PO22-Jan-10), KE58-2894F (PO11-Jun-10), and KE58-2914F (PO6-Oct-10). Two in-house reference materials were analysed during this study: (1) 21 dissolutions of a powdered rock (Kil1919) collected from the same 1919 lava flow of Kīlauea Volcano as the BHVO rock standards and (2) 37 dissolutions of a volcanic glass (called ‘Menehune’) that was quenched from a Puʻu ʻŌʻō lava flow of Kīlauea Volcano on June 24, 2006. The details of the analytical methods are described by Marske et al. (2007) and in the Supplementary Data. Briefly, the Pb isotope ratios were measured using Tl doping (SRM997) to correct for instrumental mass bias (hereafter called ‘bias’) on a Nu Plasma HR or Nu Plasma 1700 MC-ICPMS at SDSU. Analyses of SRM981 (n = 312) as a bracketing standard gave average bias-corrected values (±2σ) of 206Pb/204Pb = 16·9448 ± 52, 207Pb/204Pb = 15·5027 ± 58, and 208Pb/204Pb = 36·7349 ± 198. The bias-corrected Pb isotope ratios of the samples and in-house reference materials were normalized based on the daily bias-corrected average for SRM981 relative to the values of Galer & Abouchami (1998): 206Pb/204Pb = 16·9405, 207Pb/204Pb = 15·4963, and 208Pb/204Pb = 36·7219. The reproducibility of the 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb ratios for Kil1919 and Menehune is similar, but the reproducibility of the 206Pb/204Pb ratio for Menehune is a factor of ∼2 better than Kil1919, suggesting that Kil1919 is slightly heterogeneous. Thus, Menehune provides the best estimate for the ±2σ reproducibility of the 206Pb/204Pb (±0·0016), 207Pb/204Pb (±0·0018), and 208Pb/204Pb (±0·0060) ratios of the samples. The average in-run ±2σm errors of individual analyses were ±0·0004 for 206Pb/204Pb and 207Pb/204Pb and ±0·0011 for 208Pb/204Pb. The bias-corrected 143Nd/144Nd ratios of the samples, in-house reference materials, and the Nd isotopic standards La Jolla and JNdi-1 were normalized based on the daily bias-corrected average for the SDSU Ames Nd standard (assumed 143Nd/144Nd = 0·512130), which gave an average bias-corrected 143Nd/144Nd = 0·512106 ± 27 (±2σ, n = 244). The average bias-corrected and Ames-normalized 143Nd/144Nd ratios for the La Jolla Nd and JNdi-1 standards were 0·511843 ± 8 (±2σ, n = 55) and 0·512101 ± 7 (±2σ, n = 5), respectively. The ±2σ reproducibility for the 143Nd/144Nd ratios (±0·000008) and εεNd values (±0·15) of the samples is based on the results for Menehune. The average in-run ±2σm errors of individual analyses were ±0·000005 for 143Nd/144Nd. The εεNd values are calculated relative to 143Nd/144Nd = 0·512638 for εεNd=0. The Sr isotope ratios were measured by TIMS at SDSU (VG Sector 54) or the USGS SWIRL (Thermo Triton). The bias-corrected 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the samples and in-house reference materials were normalized based on the bias-corrected average for SRM987 from each analytical period (assumed 87Sr/86Sr = 0·710250). All of the 87Sr/86Sr ratios measured at the USGS SWIRL were performed in a single analytical period (∼8 months long), whereas the 87Sr/86Sr ratios measured at SDSU were measured over four analytical periods (each from <1 to 7 months long). Analyses of SRM987 at SDSU and the USGS SWIRL gave average bias-corrected 87Sr/86Sr ratios of 0·710248 ± 19 (±2σ, n = 196) and 0·710250 ± 7 (±2σ, n = 162), respectively. The average bias-corrected and SRM987-normalized 87Sr/86Sr ratios for each in-house reference material from SDSU and the USGS agree within ±2σm: (1) Kil1919 at SDSU gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703472 ± 16 (±2σ) with a ± 2σm error of ±0·000002 (n = 49), (2) Kil1919 at the USGS SWIRL gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703470 ± 8 (±2σ) with a ± 2σm error of ±0·000001 (n = 44), (3) Menehune at SDSU gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703618 ± 12 (±2σ) with a ± 2σm error of ±0·000002 (n = 35), and (4) Menehune at the USGS SWIRL gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703621 ± 8 (±2σ) with a ± 2σm error of ±0·000001 (n = 40). These results for Kil1919 and Menehune provide the maximum ±2σ reproducibility of the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the samples: ±0·000016 at SDSU and ±0·000008 at the USGS SWIRL. The uncertainties for the Sr isotope ratios listed in the table are based on the ±2σm (n > 2) or total range (n = 2) of the replicate analyses of each sample reported in Supplementary Data Table S3. These values represent a better (albeit imperfect) estimate for the precision of the average 87Sr/86Sr ratio of each sample than the maximum ±2σ errors defined by Kil1919 or Menehune. The average in-run ±2σm errors of individual analyses were ±0·000010 and ±0·000005 for 87Sr/86Sr at SDSU and the USGS SWIRL, respectively. The total procedural blanks for Pb (<100 pg), Sr (<140 pg), and Nd (<50 pg) were insignificant during this study.

The precision and accuracy of the isotopic measurements at SDSU (Pb, Sr, and Nd) and the USGS SWIRL (Sr) were characterized using a range of reference materials (Table 2), including high-purity single-element solution standards (SRM981 Pb, SRM987 Sr and La Jolla Nd) and two in-house Kīlauea basalt reference materials (Kil1919 and Menehune). A general discussion of error handling is provided in the Supplementary Data. Briefly, the reproducibility of the 206Pb/204Pb (±0·0016), 207Pb/204Pb (±0·0018), and 208Pb/204Pb (±0·0060) ratios, and the εεNd values (±0·15) is best represented by the ±2σ errors of the replicate Menehune analyses because the Pb and Nd isotope ratios of most samples were measured only once (see Supplementary DataTables S3 and S4 for the samples that were replicated). The Sr isotope ratio of each sample was measured more than once (n = 2–10), and the ±2σm errors (n > 2) or total range (n = 2) based on these replicate analyses is presented in Tables 2 and 3 (see Supplementary DataTables S3 and S4 for the individual 87Sr/86Sr ratios). These values (with an average of ∼0·000006, ±2σm, calculated as described in the caption to Fig. 2) represent a better (albeit imperfect) estimate for the precision of the average 87Sr/86Sr ratio of each sample than the maximum ±2 σ errors defined by Kil1919 or Menehune. In addition, we subjected each comparison or contrast of the Sr isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas to a Student’s t-test and/or analysis of variance (ANOVA) using the individual 87Sr/86Sr ratios. The results of these statistical tests are given in Supplementary DataTable S5, and the specific numerical code is cited (where appropriate) in the following discussion. Error bars on all of the figures are 2σ (equal to ±1σ) for Pb and Nd, and the average 2σm (equal to ±1σm) for Sr, and are intended only to provide a visual guide to the typical magnitude of the scatter in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios. All literature isotopic data for Hawaiian lavas and Pacific mid-ocean ridge basalts (MORB) shown on the figures or discussed in the text have been corrected relative to the same values for the SRM981 Pb (Galer & Abouchami, 1998), SRM987 Sr (87Sr/86Sr = 0·710250), and La Jolla Nd (143Nd/144Nd = 0·511843) standards for direct comparison with the results in Tables 2 and 3.

SAMPLING AND OVERVIEW OF HISTORICAL RIFT ERUPTIONS

The historical period of Kīlauea Volcano (e.g. Macdonald et al., 1983), defined here as the start of written records in August 1823, was preceded by ∼300 years of sporadic explosive summit eruptions (starting in ∼1470–1510 CE and recorded by the Keanakākoʻi Tephra) that culminated with a deadly phreatic eruption in 1790 (e.g. McPhie et al., 1990; Swanson et al., 2012) and a fire-fountaining eruption in ∼1820 (i.e. the ‘golden pumice’, which likely erupted between 1820 and 1823; Sharp et al., 1987). During the 18th century, possibly in ∼1790 (e.g. Moore & Trusdell, 1991), one or more effusive eruptions (Fig. 4) occurred on the lower ERZ (LERZ, which extends from the prehistoric Heiheiahulu lava shield to the easternmost subaerial tip of the ERZ). From August 1823 to May 1924, the volcano’s eruptive behavior was dominated by nearly continuous lava lake activity from multiple vents on the floor of Kīlauea Caldera before 1868, and from Halemaʻumaʻu alone thereafter (e.g. Brigham, 1909; Garcia, 2015). Rift eruptions occurred during this period in 1823 (SWRZ), 1840 (ERZ), 1868 (SWRZ), 1877 (ERZ), 1919–1920 (SWRZ, forming the Mauna Iki lava shield), 1922 (ERZ), and 1923 (ERZ).

In May 1924, the lava lake within Halemaʻumaʻu drained, its floor collapsed, and numerous phreatic explosions occurred. For the remainder of the 20th century (e.g. Garcia, 2015), summit eruptions from the floor of the caldera, Kīlauea Iki Crater in 1959 (Fig. 1), or Halemaʻumaʻu were sporadic (the longest hiatus was from 1934 to 1952) and relatively short (<1 day to a maximum of ∼36 weeks long for the 1967–1968 Halemaʻumaʻu lava lake activity). Two eruptions on the LERZ in 1955 (∼13 weeks) and 1960 (∼5 weeks), the first in this area since 1840, were followed by nine brief (∼1–15 day long) eruptions (Table 1) along the middle ERZ (MERZ, which extends from Nāpau Crater to Heiheiahulu) and upper ERZ (UERZ, which extends from Keanakākoʻi to Nāpau Craters) between September 1961 and February 1969 (Fig. 4). Detailed chronologies of these eruptions are presented by Moore & Krivoy (1964), Richter et al. (1964), Fiske & Koyanagi (1968), Wright et al. (1968), Moore & Koyanagi (1969), Jackson et al. (1975), Swanson et al. (1976) and Wright & Peck (1978). The 1969–1974 Mauna Ulu ERZ eruption had two major eruptive phases (May 1969 to October 1971 and February 1972 to July 1974) separated by a 3·5-month pause (Swanson et al., 1979; Tilling et al., 1987). During the Mauna Ulu eruption, additional outbreaks of lava on the rift zones occurred from: (1) a discontinuous fissure that started on the floor of the caldera near the edge of Halemaʻumaʻu and stretched ∼12 km down the SWRZ for ∼5 days in September 1971 (Duffield et al., 1982); (2) a series of subparallel fissures between the UERZ near Keanakākoʻi Crater and the southern part of the caldera in July 1974 (Lockwood et al., 1999); and (3) vents slightly uprift from Mauna Ulu at Hiʻiaka Crater in May 1973 (<1 day long) and Pauahi Crater from November to December 1973 (lasting ∼4 weeks). Subsequently, an unusual ‘eccentric’ eruption (<1 day long) from a series of fissures near the volcano’s summit between the Koaʻe fault system (KFS) and the SWRZ in December 1974 (Lockwood et al., 1999) was followed by a ∼3-week eruption along the MERZ in September 1977 (Moore et al., 1980), and a brief (<1 day long) eruption near Pauahi Crater in November 1979. One sample was analysed for its Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic composition from each rift eruption since September 1961, except for Mauna Ulu (n = 6) and July 1974 (n = 4). In addition, three samples from the December 1974 eruption were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios to complement the Pb isotopic data of Pietruszka et al. (2015).

The Puʻu ʻŌʻō MERZ eruption began in January 1983 (Wolfe et al., 1987), and represents the longest and most voluminous (>4 km3; Orr et al., 2015) historical rift eruption of Kīlauea Volcano. Previous studies (Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013; Pietruszka et al., 2015) reported high-precision Pb isotopic data for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from January 1983 to February 2012 (in addition to Sr and Nd isotope ratios for lavas from September 1998 to August 2005 in Marske et al. (2007) and Sr isotope ratios for lavas from January 1983 to January 2010 in Greene et al. (2013)). In this study, Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from January 2006 to February 2012 (n = 16, including Menehune) were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios (the Sr isotope ratios of the samples in common with Greene et al. (2013) were remeasured at SDSU or the USGS SWIRL). A lava lake (the first summit eruption since September 1982) formed within a vent on the floor of Halemaʻumaʻu (Fig. 1) following a series of small explosions in 2008 (Wilson et al., 2008). This lava lake remained active until May 2018, when it drained rapidly, the eruption of lava at Puʻu ʻŌʻō ceased, and a new eruption on the LERZ began near the 1840, 1955, and 1960 vents. At the time of this writing (July 2018), the LERZ eruption continues and volcanic ash is being emitted periodically from a widening and collapsing Halemaʻumaʻu. A detailed list of the sample locations and eruption dates is presented in Supplementary DataTable S1 for the rift lavas and Pietruszka et al. (2015) for the summit lavas.

RESULTS

Major and trace elements

Kīlauea rift lavas display a wide range in MgO with an average value of ∼8 wt % (Fig. 5a) and extend to lower MgO values (5·4 wt % in this study) than historical and young prehistoric summit lavas (6·0 wt %; Garcia et al., 2003; Marske et al., 2007; Pietruszka et al., 2013). Differentiated lavas with <7 wt % MgO that fractionated clinopyroxene±plagioclase in addition to olivine (Wright & Fiske, 1971) and olivine-controlled lavas with >7 wt % MgO (Wright, 1971), including both olivine-poor samples with up to ∼10 wt % MgO (e.g. Garcia et al., 1996) and samples that have accumulated olivine (up to the maximum MgO value of ∼14 wt% for this study), have erupted along most of the ERZ. Lavas with <6 wt % MgO are mostly restricted to the MERZ (in September 1977 and rarely during the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption; Garcia et al., 1989; Thornber et al., 2003, 2015) and LERZ (in 1955 and 1960; Wright & Fiske, 1971; Ho & Garcia, 1988; Helz & Wright, 1992; Wright & Helz, 1996). The September 1971 SWRZ lava is olivine controlled (7·7 wt % MgO), although some of the most differentiated lavas known from Kīlauea (down to 3·9 wt % MgO) erupted from or near the SWRZ in prehistoric times (Wright & Fiske, 1971; Anderson & Wright, 1972). Lavas from the eccentric December 1974 eruption are rich in MgO (12·1–15·7 wt %) and olivine (Lockwood et al., 1999; Garcia et al., 2003). Differentiated lavas make up ∼17% of the total number of samples from Kīlauea’s rift zones, excluding the large number of dominantly olivine-controlled Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas. This proportion of differentiated rift lavas is probably an underestimate because no LERZ lavas from 1955 or 1960 were analysed in this study. A significant proportion (∼33%) of differentiated lavas have also erupted at the volcano’s summit (Fig. 5b), which confirms (in contrast to early studies; Wright, 1971; Wright & Fiske, 1971) that summit lavas are not strictly olivine controlled (Garcia et al., 2003).

Histograms of the MgO abundances of lavas from the (a) rift zones and (b) summit of Kīlauea Volcano. The rift zone XRF data shown in (a) include samples from Supplementary DataTable S2, the eccentric December 1974 lavas from Garcia et al. (2003), and Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from Greene et al. (2013). The average MgO value (and range) for each group of lavas excludes samples with ≥13 wt % MgO that likely accumulated olivine.

Kīlauea summit lavas display systematic temporal variations in ratios of incompatible elements. For example, the Nb/Y (Fig. 6a) or K2O/TiO2 (Fig. 6b) ratios of young prehistoric lavas from the caldera wall (Fig. 1) at Uwēkahuna Bluff (∼1000–1400 CE) and samples from the Keanakākoʻi Tephra (∼1650–1700 CE) are relatively low. The Nb/Y and K2O/TiO2 ratios of summit lavas increased from the early 19th century to the late 19th century. Summit lavas from the early to mid-20th century have even higher Nb/Y at a given K2O/TiO2 ratio. Thereafter, the K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios of summit lavas (with lower Nb/Y at a given K2O/TiO2 ratio) decreased for the remainder of the 20th century (1961 to 1982). Tephra glasses from Halemaʻumaʻu in 2008 (Thornber et al., 2015) have K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios that are similar to the prehistoric and early 19th century lavas. The chemistry of most rift lavas (for example, when grouped broadly into the 1960s, the 1970s, and 2010–2012 Puʻu ʻŌʻō) is similar to contemporaneous summit lavas. In contrast, the September 1977 ERZ lava (Nb/Y = 0.71) and early Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1983 to 1985 (Nb/Y up to ∼0·78) are chemically distinct from the nearly contemporaneous 1982 summit lavas (Nb/Y = 0·56–0·59).

Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions

Lavas erupted over the last millennium at Kīlauea’s summit display a systematic fluctuation in their Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007). The highest 206Pb/204Pb and lowest 87Sr/86Sr ratios are observed in summit lavas from the early 20th century (Fig. 2). Between 1919 and 1929, probably after the collapse of the Halemaʻumaʻu lava lake in 1924, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of summit lavas shifted to lower and higher values, respectively (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). This shift is illustrated by the different 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the 1919 and 1959 summit lavas. For the rest of the 20th century (1961 to 1982), the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas decreased, whereas their Sr isotope ratios varied only slightly. Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1986 to 2012, after the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ (Garcia et al., 1992), continue these trends: (1) a temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb followed by cyclic variations over a narrow range on a time scale of <10 years (Greene et al., 2013); and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr to a maximum of ∼0.70364 between ∼2000 and 2003 and a slight decrease thereafter (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013). Tephra glasses from Halemaʻumaʻu in 2009 and 2010 (Table 3) record the lowest 206Pb/204Pb (18.39–18.40) and highest 87Sr/86Sr (0·70361–0·70362) ratios for summit lavas since the early 19th century (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). The Pb and Sr isotope ratios of rift lavas (Fig. 2) may be either: (1) broadly similar to (e.g. the 1960s, 1970s, and 2010–2012 Puʻu ʻŌʻō) or (2) distinct from (e.g. the September 1977 ERZ lava and early Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1983 to 1985) contemporaneous summit lavas. These isotopic similarities and differences are the major focus of this study.

Compared to the Uwēkahuna Bluff lavas, most historical Kīlauea lavas have lower 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 7a), similar εNd values (Fig. 7b), and higher Pb isotope ratios (Fig. 7c and d). On plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs208Pb/204Pb or 207Pb/204Pb, summit and rift lavas lie along tight arrays, except for: (1) the lower 208Pb/204Pb at a given 206Pb/204Pb of the 1919 summit lava; (2) three Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (erupted on 7-Sep-98, 13-Feb-99, and 19-Jun-99) from Greene et al. (2013) with anomalously high 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) that were not observed in two of the same samples analysed by Marske et al. (2008); (3) another Puʻu ʻŌʻō lava erupted in April 1983 (KE3-117) from Greene et al. (2013) with high 207Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb); (4) high 207Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) for ERZ lavas from August 1963 (DPH-77) and July 1974 (J1974-EV); and (5) low 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) for the 2010 Halemaʻumaʻu tephra glasses. These observations based on the Pb-Pb diagrams are discussed further in the Supplementary Data. Overall (Fig. 7a), Kīlauea lavas display a broad negative correlation on a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr (the ‘Kīlauea best-fit line’), although samples from the mid- to late-20th century show a positive correlation. No simple relationships are observed for Kīlauea lavas on a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs εNd (Fig. 7b). The majority of the samples cluster around an εNd value of +6·2. The 1919 summit lava has a slightly higher εNd value (+6·5), whereas summit lavas from 1959 and the most recent rift (Puʻu ʻŌʻō after 1986) and summit (2009–2010 Halemaʻumaʻu) samples have slightly lower average εNd values (+6.0).

THE MAGMA BATCH HYPOTHESIS

Olivine-controlled Kīlauea lavas from historical summit eruptions display small differences in their SiO2, CaO, K2O, and TiO2 abundances at a given MgO (e.g. Wright, 1971) that are thought to result from short-term changes in the composition of the parental magma delivered to the volcano’s summit reservoir (e.g. Garcia et al., 2003). Based on these observations, the classic ‘magma batch’ hypothesis for Kīlauea states that individual batches of compositionally distinct magma from the mantle are tapped by each summit eruption, and that summit eruptions tend to end when a particular magma batch has been exhausted (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright & Klein, 2014). The magma batch hypothesis is illustrated by a Nb/Y–K2O/TiO2 diagram (Fig. 6b), where summit lavas plot in distinct fields that vary systematically as a function of eruption date. On this plot, for example, each of the three contemporaneous groups of chemically similar summit and rift lavas may (in principle) have been derived from the same magma batch (i.e. three magma batches, corresponding to the 1960s, the 1970s, and 2010–2012 Puʻu ʻŌʻō). In contrast, the September 1977 ERZ lava and early Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1983 to 1985 must have at least one component of magma that is chemically distinct from the nearly contemporaneous 1982 summit lavas. Based on their broad similarity to the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit lavas, this additional magma component is most likely summit-derived magma that was stored in the ERZ since the 1960s.

A detailed eruption-by-eruption comparison of the major element abundances of both olivine-controlled and differentiated Kīlauea lavas (often including least-squares mass-balance modeling) has been used to identify the transport, mixing, and storage of summit-derived magma batches within the rift zones (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980; Wright & Helz, 1996). This approach works best for olivine-controlled lavas. However, the major element abundances of many summit and rift lavas (Fig. 5) have been affected (at least slightly) by differentiation beyond olivine control. For example, clinopyroxene(±plagioclase) fractionation strongly decreases the CaO/TiO2 ratios of lavas with <7 wt % MgO (Fig. 6c). Multiphase crystal fractionation has clearly modified the chemistry of the September 1977 ERZ lava and the most evolved lavas from the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption (based on their low CaO/TiO2 ratios), but it may have cryptically affected the whole-rock major element abundances of nominally olivine-controlled lavas with >7 wt % MgO if olivine was subsequently added to a differentiated magma. This type of cryptic process is suggested (for example) by the wide range in CaO/TiO2 for the 1960s rift lavas (∼3·6–4·4) despite their relatively high MgO contents (all but one sample have >7 wt % MgO). Crystal fractionation (beyond olivine control) likely complicates the identification of magma batches using the major element abundances of Kīlauea lavas. We focus on the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the lavas, which are not affected by magmatic differentiation and have a higher proportion of signal to noise than the major element abundances (at a given MgO value) and incompatible element ratios.

EVALUATION OF CRUSTAL CONTAMINATION

The overall Pb, Sr and Nd isotopic variations of Kīlauea lavas (Fig. 7) require the derivation of melt from at least three distinct mantle components within the Hawaiian plume, which is thought to be heterogeneous (e.g. Tatsumoto, 1978; Abouchami et al., 2005; Weis et al., 2011) on a small scale (e.g. Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013). However, the potential effects of crustal contamination must be evaluated before the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of Kīlauea lavas can be used to identify magma batches from the mantle and track their movement though the ERZ and/or SWRZ.

Kīlauea magmas may be contaminated by the Pacific oceanic crust and/or the Hawaiian volcanic edifice. The Pacific oceanic crust may include a variety of materials, ranging from the variably altered mid-ocean ridge basalts and/or gabbros that comprise the Cretaceous igneous basement (which is expected to be depleted in highly incompatible elements like Pb) to marine sediments, ferromanganese (Fe-Mn) nodules, and hydrothermal minerals that may be rich in Pb, Sr, and/or Nd. The Hawaiian volcanic edifice may include: (1) older lava flows from Kīlauea and/or Mauna Loa, which directly underlie the summit region of Kīlauea; (2) partially or completely solidified bodies of Kīlauea magma (now gabbro) that may contain veins of highly evolved residual melt (or glass, if solidified); and (3) olivine-rich cumulates, which may also contain a small amount of interstitial Kīlauea melt (or glass). In the Supplementary Data and Supplementary Data Table S6, each type of contaminant is evaluated in detail as a potential control on the relatively small isotopic shifts that are used to identify and track magma batches. Below, we demonstrate that the overall Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic variations of Kīlauea lavas (represented by the best-fit lines on Fig. 7) are not controlled by crustal contamination. This discussion expands on similar conclusions by Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) using the much larger amount of isotopic data (including high-precision Pb isotope ratios) that are now available for both Kīlauea and Mauna Loa lavas.

Assimilation of materials within the Hawaiian volcanic edifice

The strongest evidence for crustal contamination of Kīlauea magmas comes from the variable and low δ18O values of some lavas (down to ∼4·6‰) that are most likely caused by interaction between magma and hydrothermally altered country rocks (with δ18O values of ∼2·6‰ or less) from Kīlauea and/or Mauna Loa (Garcia et al., 1998, 2008). Cannibalization of old Kīlauea lavas or gabbros, or olivine cumulates±trapped melt or glass would probably sample a random mixture of materials with a net isotopic composition similar to the average of Kīlauea lavas on Fig. 7 (206Pb/204Pb = 18·44 and 87Sr/86Sr = 0·70359). This process (if extensive) would dampen the rapid temporal variations in the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas, rather than produce the extremes that are observed at Uwēkahuna Bluff and in 1919. It is difficult to explain even the smaller isotopic shifts, such as the one observed immediately after the 1924 explosive eruption of Halemaʻumaʻu (Fig. 2), by cannibalization. For example, Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) modeled this post-1924 decrease in 206Pb/204Pb and increase in 87Sr/86Sr due to the contamination of magma within the volcano’s summit reservoir by highly evolved residual glass in gabbros from stoped country rock following the collapse and enlargement of Halemaʻumaʻu by ∼0·2 km3 in 1924 (notably, both ratios moved closer to average Kīlauea values from 1919 to 1959; Fig. 7a). However, it is much easier to explain these observations (for the reasons outlined in the Supplementary Data) if the post-1924 lavas represent a new parental magma that formed by relatively low degrees of partial melting (based on their higher Nb/Y ratios; Fig. 6a) of a mantle source that is isotopically distinct from the source of the early 20th century summit lavas.

Mauna Loa lavas (e.g. Weis et al., 2011) tend to have lower Pb isotope ratios (with more scatter in 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb at a given 207Pb/204Pb), higher 87Sr/86Sr ratios, and lower εNd values than Kīlauea lavas (Fig. 8). Variable assimilation of old Mauna Loa lava flows by a ‘high 206Pb/204Pb Kīlauea end-member’ magma might create the range in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of other Kīlauea lavas. However, most Mauna Loa lavas are an inappropriate choice for a contaminant because they have 87Sr/86Sr ratios that are too high (Fig. 8a) and εNd values that are too low (Fig. 8b). Even if an optimized Mauna Loa contaminant on the Kīlauea best-fit lines is chosen (such as the purple pentagon in Fig. 8), a large amount of bulk assimilation (≥60% for historical Kīlauea lavas) would be required.

Assimilation of materials from the Pacific oceanic crust

Assimilation of materials from the Pacific oceanic crust is probably restricted to a depth of ≥10 km beneath Kīlauea’s summit region, based on estimates for the thickness of a typical Hawaiian volcanic edifice (e.g. DePaolo & Stolper, 1996). This is much deeper than the volcano’s shallow plumbing system (Fig. 3), which lies at a depth of ∼4 km or less (e.g. Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Poland et al., 2014). As long as any assimilation of the Pacific oceanic crust by mantle-derived Kīlauea magma occurs within the primary conduit at a depth of >4 km, the contaminated magma is likely to be first delivered to the summit reservoir before intruding the rift zones. In this case, the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of the contaminated magma may be used (as if these signatures were derived from the mantle) to identify and track magma batches. This would be the most likely scenario for nearly all Kīlauea lavas. However, deeper intrusions of magma may extend to a depth of ∼9–10 km (Delaney et al., 1990), which would potentially intersect the uppermost portion of the Pacific oceanic crust. If this represents a zone of magma transport that may bypass the summit reservoir, then contaminated magma could erupt directly along the rift zones with Pb, Sr, and/or Nd isotope ratios unlike contemporaneous summit lavas.

The Cretaceous igneous basement that underlies the Island of Hawaiʻi formed ≤110 Ma ago at a mid-ocean ridge spreading center (Waggoner, 1993), and thus, might be represented by the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios (Fig. 9) of young (‘fresh’) Pacific MORB and/or drilled, altered basalts from Site 843 of the Ocean Drilling Program located in the central Pacific Ocean ∼400 km west of Kīlauea (King et al., 1993; Fekiacova et al., 2007). The Pb, Sr, and Nd concentrations of these basalts and associated gabbros are expected to be similar to or lower than lower than Kīlauea magmas (Supplementary DataTable S6). Thus, an enormous amount of bulk assimilation of the igneous basement would be required to explain the total range in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). This can probably be reduced only if the process of assimilation is dominated by the addition of low degree partial melts of crystalline gabbros.

Melting of the lower crust (related either to the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the underlying Cretaceous igneous basement) may be an important process during the late shield to postshield stages of some Hawaiian volcanoes (e.g. Frey et al., 1990; Gaffney et al., 2004; van der Zander et al., 2010), a period of rapidly declining or low magma supply. Few studies (e.g. Hegner et al., 1986; Stille et al., 1986) have explicitly considered the possibility that Hawaiian magmas may originate within or assimilate (in bulk or as a partial melt) the Cretaceous igneous basement during the main shield stage of a Hawaiian volcano, when the rate of magma supply is at a maximum. Most recently, Eiler et al. (1996) suggested that the low δ18O values of some olivine phenocrysts in Hawaiian shield basalts (all from the so-called ‘Kea’ spatial trend of volcanoes, which includes Kīlauea and Mauna Kea) are related to the assimilation of hydrothermally altered Pacific oceanic crust by mantle-derived Hawaiian magma (also noting, like Tatsumoto (1978), the broad similarity between the Pb isotope ratios of Kea-trend lavas and Pacific MORB). Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) subsequently argued that the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas could not be explained either by: (1) melting of the ambient upper mantle lithosphere (e.g. Tatsumoto, 1978) or asthenosphere (e.g. Hauri, 1996; Lassiter et al., 1996) beneath Hawaiʻi or (2) bulk assimilation of the Cretaceous igneous basement (represented either by Pacific MORB or the Site 843 basalts). Instead, the ‘Kīlauea’ isotopic end member with relatively high 206Pb/204Pb and low 87Sr/86Sr ratios and a high εNd value (Fig. 8) most likely results from the melting of a long-term depleted mantle component within the Hawaiian plume (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Pietruszka et al., 2013).

The high-precision Pb isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas (along with their Sr and Nd isotope ratios) relative to Pacific MORB and Site 843 basalts support the interpretation of Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a). The most common 206Pb/204Pb ratios for Pacific MORB, ranging from ∼18·0 to 18·9 with an average value of ∼18·5, overlap with Kīlauea lavas (Fig. 9). However, Pacific MORB have (on average) lower 208Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9a), and especially, higher 207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) ratios than Kīlauea lavas (at a given 206Pb/204Pb), and the Kīlauea best-fit line on each Pb-Pb diagram is shallower than the array for Pacific MORB. Furthermore, the best-fit trend of Kīlauea lavas is strongly orthogonal to the Pacific MORB array on plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs εNd (Fig. 9c and d) or 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9e and f). This divergence eliminates the (already remote) possibility that the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas are related to the assimilation of the Cretaceous igneous basement or melting of the ambient mantle lithosphere or asthenosphere beneath Hawaiʻi, if any of these components may be accurately represented by Pacific MORB.

The Cretaceous igneous basement has probably been altered by seawater and/or hydrothermal fluids and, thus, might be better represented by the Site 843 basalts (King et al., 1993; Fekiacova et al., 2007). These samples (all of which were acid leached prior to digestion in the laboratory, and thus, probably under-represent the extent of post-eruptive alteration) trend towards higher 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than most Pacific MORB with similar 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb ratios and εNd values (Fig. 9). Post-eruptive alteration of the Site 843 basalts is the most likely cause of the elevated 206Pb/204Pb (due to variable U enrichment of the rock during alteration and post-eruptive decay of the 238U over ∼110 Myr) and 87Sr/86Sr (due to direct alteration of the rock with radiogenic Sr from seawater) ratios (Fekiacova et al., 2007). The most altered Site 843 basalts could serve as an approximate contaminant of Kīlauea magmas (as defined by the best-fit lines), at least with respect to the plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) or (roughly) 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9f). However, their 208Pb/204Pb ratios are too low (Fig. 9a) and εNd values are (probably) too high (Fig. 9d) to represent either a potential bulk (basaltic) or partially melted (gabbroic) contaminant. These observations exclude the possibility that bulk assimilation of the altered Cretaceous igneous basement (if accurately represented by the most altered Site 843 basalts) controls the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas.

Marine sediments (e.g. pelagic clay, chert, and carbonate), Fe–Mn nodules (or crusts), and hydrothermal minerals (mainly sulfides and sulfide-rich sediments) are important, but volumetrically minor, components of the Pacific oceanic crust (Fig. 9). Neither marine sediments nor Fe–Mn nodules are appropriate contaminants to create the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of Kīlauea lavas because both of these materials: (1) have high 208Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9a), and especially, 207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) at a given 206Pb/204Pb, and lie completely above the Kīlauea best-fit line on each Pb–Pb diagram; and (2) have εNd values and 87Sr/86Sr ratios that are orthogonal to the trend of Kīlauea lavas on plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs εNd (Fig. 9c) or 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9e). The average 206Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb ratios of hydrothermal minerals (representing the most likely isotopic composition for this potential contaminant) are similar to the high 206Pb/204Pb Kīlauea end-member, but their average 207Pb/204Pb (∼15·54) is far too high to explain the overall trend of Kīlauea lavas on the 206Pb/204Pb–207Pb/204Pb diagram (Fig. 9b).

We conclude that crustal contamination of mantle-derived Kīlauea magmas by the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the Pacific oceanic crust does not control the overall Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic variations of Kīlauea lavas. As discussed in the Supplementary Data, even the relatively small isotopic shifts are most likely derived (with the additional effects of magma mixing) from the delivery of compositionally distinct magma batches from the mantle.

MAGMA BATCHES AND THE SUMMIT RESERVOIR OF KĪLAUEA VOLCANO

Many magma batches have been identified for eruptions at the summit of Kīlauea Volcano during the mid- to late 20th century based on the major element abundances of the lavas (e.g. Helz et al., 2014; Wright & Klein, 2014). For example, nine compositionally distinct batches of mantle-derived magma were inferred from summit lavas erupted in 1952, 1954, 1959, 1961, 1967–1968, 1971, 1974, 1975, and 1982 (Helz et al., 2014), which amounts to one for each eruption. In this section, we summarize an alternative view of the number of magma batches from 1959 to 1982 based on modeling of the temporal mixing trends defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Kīlauea summit lavas (Fig. 10).

Fig. 10.

The width of the box indicates the maximum range in the initial time of magma input, and the height of the box represents the maximum range in its 206Pb/204Pb ratio. The best-fit mixing curves are shown in black, whereas the widest permissible range of model parameters were used to calculate the grey mixing curves [see Pietruszka et al. (2015) for details]. A single mixing trend accounts for the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas from 1959 to 1968, but two mixing trends (‘upper’ and ‘lower’) are required for summit lavas from 1971 to 1982. The data sources are the same as in Fig. 7. The 2σ error bars are smaller than the size of the symbols.

A detailed explanation of the model derivation, assumptions, and results was presented by Pietruszka et al. (2015). Briefly, a residence time model for incompatible elements (Albarède, 1993) was modified for use with isotope ratios. This model assumes that the temporal change in the mass of magma in a chamber (⁠M⁠) is controlled by the balance between: (1) a constant rate of magma input (⁠Qin⁠) with a constant Pb concentration (⁠Cin⁠) and 206Pb/204Pb ratio (⁠Rin⁠) from the mantle or a deeper chamber; (2) a constant rate of magma output (⁠Qout⁠) to eruptions at the volcano’s summit and/or withdrawals to the rift zones; and (3) a constant rate of crystallization (⁠X⁠). If the magma in the chamber is assumed to be well mixed (as suggested by Gerlach et al. (2002)), the equation used to model the residence time of magma in the chamber is
ατααταταατRt=R0C0Cine-αt/τ+Rinα1-e-αt/τC0Cine-αt/τ+1α1-e-αt/τ,
(1)
where Rt is the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the erupted lava at a given time (⁠t⁠), R0 is the initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the chamber magma, C0 is the initial Pb concentration of the chamber magma, and ττ is the magma residence time. The effects of crystal fractionation are described by αα=1+fx×DPb-1⁠, where DPb is the bulk partition coefficient of Pb and fx is the fraction of the input magma flux that is lost to crystallization (⁠fx=X/Qin⁠). Magma within Kīlauea’s summit reservoir since the mid-20th century has been dominantly olivine controlled (Garcia et al., 2003; Wright, 1971). Since Pb is highly incompatible in olivine, DPb= 0 and αα=1-fx⁠. In order to calculate the volume of magma in the chamber from the definition of magma residence time (⁠ττ=M/Qin⁠), an estimate of the magma supply rate (⁠Qin⁠) is required. The densities of the input and chamber magmas are assumed to be equal. In this case, the magma residence time can be expressed in terms of magma volume (⁠V⁠) and a volumetric supply rate (⁠Qinv⁠). Thus, the final equation used to calculate the volume of magma in the chamber is τV=τ×Qinv⁠.

The modeling was performed by Pietruszka et al. (2015) to best match the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the lavas for a given temporal mixing trend (excluding the samples used to define the R0 values) by iteratively varying the residence time (⁠ττ⁠) and 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the input magma (⁠Rin⁠) for a wide range of C0/Cin and αα values. This approach leads to 20 model permutations for each mixing trend (i.e. best-fit, highest and lowest permissible Rin⁠, and longest and shortest permissible ττ⁠, each at the maximum and minimum assumed limits of C0/Cin and αα⁠) that are collectively thought to provide estimates of the reasonable extremes in the ττ and Rin values that are permitted (within the ±4σ error) by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the lavas. These model limits for Rin and ττ are listed in the following summary.

Kīlauea summit lavas define a single temporal trend of decreasing 206Pb/204Pb ratios from 1959 to 1968 (Fig. 10a) that can be modeled by the progressive mixing of two compositionally distinct magmas within the volcano’s summit reservoir (both the HMM and SC bodies, which were probably well connected during this period). This magma mixing trend can be explained if a new batch of mantle-derived magma with a relatively low and constant 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·49–18·50 was first delivered to the summit reservoir between 1959 and 1961 (#1 on Fig. 10a), and continuously mixed with the resident magma (initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18.60) until 1968. The mixing model for the 1959–1968 period gives a best-fit magma residence time of ∼2·4–3·1 yr (maximum range of ∼2·3–3·2 yr), which corresponds to a magma volume of only ∼0·1–0·3 km3 (0·1–0·4 km3 maximum range) assuming a range of magma supply rates to the summit reservoir from ∼0·06 km3/yr for the 1959–1990 period to ∼0·11 km3/yr for the early years of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption (Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993).

From 1971 to 1982, Kīlauea summit lavas define two separate trends of decreasing 206Pb/204Pb ratios (Fig. 10b). During this period, summit eruptions occurred near Halemaʻumaʻu (September 1971, September 1974, 1975, and April 1982), on the caldera floor (September 1982), or from fissures that extended from the caldera floor towards the UERZ near Keakakākoʻi Crater (August 1971 and July 1974). The ‘upper’ trend with higher 206Pb/204Pb at a given time is defined by one of the lavas from September 1982, and all of the summit lavas that erupted from vents near Halemaʻumaʻu or the westernmost end of the fissures on the caldera floor in August 1971 and July 1974. The ‘lower’ trend with lower 206Pb/204Pb at a given time is defined by two of the lavas from September 1982 and the easternmost summit lavas that erupted in August 1971 and July 1974, either on the floor of the caldera or on the caldera rim northwest of Keakakākoʻi Crater. Each of the temporal trends in 206Pb/204Pb from 1971 to 1982 can be modeled by the progressive mixing of two compositionally distinct magmas within separate bodies.

The locations of the two magma bodies are inferred to coincide with the two major deformation centers beneath Kīlauea’s summit region (Fig. 1): (1) the deeper SC body for the ‘lower’ mixing trend; and (2) the poorly connected (since at least August 1971), shallower HMM body for the ‘upper’ mixing trend (which is thought to receive magma only from the SC body). For example, the ‘lower’ trend of magma mixing can be explained if a second batch of mantle-derived magma with a relatively low and constant 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·45–18·46 was first delivered to the SC body between 1968 and August 1971 (#2 on Fig. 10a), and continuously mixed with the resident magma (initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18.49) until September 1982. The mixing model for the lower-trend lavas gives a best-fit magma residence time of ∼1·8–2·4 yr (maximum range of ∼1·5–2·9 yr), which corresponds to a magma volume of ∼0·1–0·3 km3 (0·09–0.3 km3 maximum range) for the SC body, assuming a ∼0·06–0·11 km3/yr range in the rate of magma supply to the summit reservoir. In contrast, the mixing model for the upper-trend lavas gives a longer best-fit magma residence time of ∼5·9–8·3 yr (maximum range of ∼3·9–20·6 yr). This value is poorly constrained because the shallow HMM body was supplied from the deeper SC magma body, which was evolving in its Pb isotopic composition on a similar time scale. Pietruszka et al. (2015) estimated that only ∼0·01–0·03 km3/yr of magma was delivered to the HMM body from 1971 to 1982, corresponding to a magma volume of ∼0·06–0·2 km3 (∼0·04–0·6 km3 maximum range). The sum of the best-fit magma volumes for the 1971–1982 period is ∼0·2–0·5 km3, representing the volume of magma within the entire summit reservoir.

This modeling suggests that: (1) as few as two compositionally distinct mantle-derived magma batches were delivered to the summit reservoir from 1959 to 1982 (#1 and #2 in Fig. 10a), instead of the seven batches identified by Helz et al. (2014) for this period; and (2) most of the other differences in the chemistry of summit lavas erupted during the late 20th century (beyond the effects of crystal fractionation or accumulation) are related to magma mixing within the summit reservoir. This interpretation will be refined based on the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of summit and rift lavas since 1959, as shown in Fig. 11.

Fig. 11.
Open in new tabDownload slide

Schematic diagram of the magma mixing components for the summit and rift eruptions of Kīlauea Volcano since 1959 (circles and ovals). The relative positions of the August 1971 SWRZ lava and summit lavas from 1971 to 1982 are shown (rectangles).

The two separate trends in 206Pb/204Pb for Kīlauea summit lavas from 1971 to 1982 correlate with differences in MgO. For each of the summit eruptions in August 1971, July 1974, and September 1982, the lavas with the lowest 206Pb/204Pb ratios (derived from the SC body) have higher MgO contents (by ∼2–3 wt %) than the lavas with the highest 206Pb/204Pb ratios (derived from the HMM body). These differences in MgO probably reflect a higher pre-eruptive temperature [up to ∼40°C based on the MgO geothermometer of Helz & Thornber (1987)] for the magma in the deeper SC body compared to the shallower HMM body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Two distinct peaks are visible on a histogram of the MgO contents of a larger number of historical and young prehistoric Kīlauea summit lavas (Fig. 5b). If the data are divided at ∼8 wt % MgO, a narrower peak can be defined at ∼7 wt % MgO and a wider peak can be defined at ∼10 wt % MgO. The predominance of the narrower peak at ∼7 wt % MgO (representing ∼76% of summit lavas) may result from the thermal and compositional buffering of magma that is ‘perched’ at the boundary between olivine control and the multiphase crystallization of olivine and clinopyroxene±plagioclase (Rhodes, 1988). Although some of the summit lavas with >8 wt % MgO may have accumulated a small amount of olivine, crystal-free Kīlauea glasses with relatively high MgO contents (up to ∼9–12 wt %) from prehistoric explosive eruptions (including the Keanakākaoʻi Tephra) and summit eruptions in ∼1820, 1924, 1959, August 1971, and July 1974 have been discovered (Helz, 1987; Garcia et al., 2003; Helz et al., 2014, Swanson et al., 2014; Helz et al., 2015). A wide range in the MgO contents of these glasses (often found within a single eruption) was interpreted by Helz et al. (2015) to result from the storage of magma at different levels beneath the summit of the volcano (with the high-MgO melts erupting directly from a greater depth). The higher average MgO content of rift lavas (∼8 wt %; Fig. 5a) compared to the summit lavas that (since at least 1971) are inferred to have tapped the shallower, cooler HMM body (∼7 wt %; Fig. 5b), supports the idea of Poland et al. (2014) that ERZ lavas are supplied from the deeper, hotter SC body. This model for Kīlauea’s summit reservoir (Fig. 3) is used for the remainder of this study, but alternative models are evaluated in the Supplementary Data.

THE VOLCANIC SOUTHWEST RIFT ZONE (1971)

Historical eruptions along Kīlauea’s volcanic SWRZ (called simply the ‘SWRZ’ for the remainder of this section) occurred in 1823, 1868, 1919–1920 (Mauna Iki), and September 1971. Lava erupted from a series of fissures in September 1971 that propagated from Halemaʻumaʻu and the floor of the caldera down the SWRZ (Duffield et al., 1982), ending near the Mauna Iki lava shield (Fig. 4). This eruption represents a simple test of the ability of Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios to track the migration of magma within Kīlauea’s plumbing system. The isotopic composition (Fig. 7), and K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios (Fig. 6b) of the olivine-controlled September 1971 SWRZ lava (7·7 wt % MgO) are similar to the September 1971 summit lavas. Notably, the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the September 1971 SWRZ lava (Fig. 10b) is: (1) nearly identical to contemporaneous summit lavas from the ‘upper’ Pb temporal trend (i.e. the September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas, all of which erupted near Halemaʻumaʻu); and (2) distinct from the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas, which define the ‘lower’ Pb temporal trend at this time. A similar observation holds for the Sr isotope ratios (Fig. 12). The similar 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas (t-test #1) are indistinguishable from the September 1971 SWRZ lava (t-test #2). In contrast, the 87Sr/86Sr ratio of the September 1971 SWRZ lava is distinct from the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #3). Thus, the September 1971 SWRZ lava was likely supplied from the shallow HMM body rather than the deeper SC body. This magma may have been transported directly from the HMM body to the SWRZ at a deep level (Fig. 3) and/or it may have been delivered to the SWRZ via a near-surface dike from just beneath Halemaʻumaʻu (e.g. Duffield et al., 1982; Poland et al., 2014). These observations suggest that the September 1971 SWRZ lavas were derived from the summit reservoir (most likely the HMM body) shortly before the eruption (i.e. little or no pre-eruptive magma storage within the SWRZ). Our logic for the SWRZ, as well as the other summit and rift eruptions, is illustrated in Supplementary Data Fig. S1.

THE UPPER TO MIDDLE EAST RIFT ZONE (1961–1974)

Eruptions of the 1960s

From September 1961 to February 1969, Kīlauea experienced nine short-lived (≤15 day long) eruptions (Table 1) along the UERZ and MERZ (Fig. 4), most of which coincided with deflations of the volcano’s summit region (Wright & Klein, 2014). These 1960s ERZ lavas have a relatively narrow, 6·7–8·0 wt % range in MgO (Supplementary DataTable S2), except for the samples from August 1968 (a picrite with 14·2 wt % MgO; Jackson et al., 1975) and February 1969 (up to 9·6 wt % MgO and ∼6 vol. % olivine phenocrysts; Swanson et al., 1976). The CaO/TiO2 ratios (Fig. 6c) of the 1960s ERZ lavas (3·6–4·3, excluding the August 1968 picrite) are similar to or lower than lavas from the olivine-controlled 1961 and 1967–1968 summit eruptions (4·1–4·2), suggesting that some of them may have fractionated clinopyroxene(±plagioclase) and/or mixed with a differentiated, rift-stored magma (and, in either case, subsequently accumulated a small amount of olivine). In contrast, the K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios (Fig. 6b) of the 1960s ERZ lavas (0·196–0·209 and 0·63–0·72, respectively) overlap with the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit lavas (0·197–0·207 and 0·64–0·72, respectively).

The 1960s ERZ lavas display a scattered temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb (with values between the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit lavas; Fig. 13a) that plot within error of or slightly above the magma mixing trend defined by summit lavas from 1959 to 1968 (Fig. 10a). This observation is consistent with the idea (based on major element abundances; Wright & Fiske, 1971) that the 1960s ERZ lavas are mixtures of magmas similar to the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit lavas with a temporal increase in the relative amount of the 1967–1968 type of summit magma. This mixing probably occurred mostly within the summit reservoir between a resident magma similar to the most primitive 1959 Kīlauea Iki lavas and a mantle-derived input magma (#1 on Fig. 10a) with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio that began entering the summit reservoir between 1959 and 1961 (Pietruszka et al., 2015). The 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this input magma (#1 on Fig. 12) must have been similar to the average of lavas from the 1959 Kīlauea Iki eruption in order to explain the relatively constant (and similar) values for the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit lavas, and most of the 1960s ERZ lavas except for the August 1968 picrite (t-tests #4 and #5, and ANOVA #1). The 1960s ERZ lavas that plot above the temporal mixing trend defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas were likely removed from the summit reservoir and (1) stored for short periods of time within the ERZ prior to eruption and/or (2) mixed with one or more slightly older rift-stored magma(s). Summit-derived magma from the early 20th century (similar to the 1919 summit lava) cannot serve as a mixing component for the 1960s ERZ lavas because its 206Pb/204Pb ratio is too high and its 87Sr/86Sr ratio is too low (Fig. 7a). Thus, Kīlauea’s UERZ and MERZ were most likely primed with a large amount of 1960s-era summit-derived magma by the end of the decade.
