August 1968 eruption

The August 1968 picrite, which initially erupted from Hiʻiaka Crater on the UERZ (Jackson et al., 1975), is unusual because it has a slightly lower 87Sr/86Sr ratio (Fig. 12) than the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit and other 1960s ERZ lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #6). The Sr isotope ratio of the Aug. 1968 sample (HI68-02) was analysed four times, giving an average 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703566 ± 5 (±2σm). This value is lower than (1) the four lavas from the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit eruptions, which gave an average 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703577 ± 2 (±2σm) for 11 replicate analyses, and (2) the other 1960s ERZ lavas, which also gave an average 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703577 ± 2 (±2σm) for 36 replicate analyses. The slightly elevated 206Pb/204Pb ratio (18·521) of the August 1968 picrite (compared to 18·503–18·508 for the 1967–1968 summit lavas that erupted shortly before it) indicates that this lava must have at least one component of magma that was stored in the ERZ since the mid- to late-1960s (Fig. 10a), hereafter called the ‘stored 1960s magma component’ (Fig. 13b). However, an additional magma mixing component is required to explain its low Sr isotope ratio compared to the other lavas from the 1960s.

It is possible that: (1) a new mantle-derived magma with a relatively low 87Sr/86Sr was delivered to the summit reservoir immediately after the end of the 1967–1968 summit eruption (in July 1968), where it mixed with the resident magma; and (2) the magma within the summit reservoir just prior to the August 1968 eruption (now with a lower 87Sr/86Sr) intruded the ERZ and mixed with the stored 1960s magma component to create the August 1968 picrite. However, it is unlikely that even this small shift in 87Sr/86Sr could have occurred in such a short period of time (<2 months) due to: (1) the buffering capacity of the estimated ∼0·1–0·3 km3 of magma within the summit reservoir during the 1960s (Pietruszka et al., 2015); and (2) the fact that the Sr isotope ratio of the newly mixed magma within the summit reservoir (just before it was withdrawn to the ERZ) would have to be even lower than the August 1968 picrite in order to match its 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios after additional mixing with the stored 1960s magma component (Fig. 13b). Wright et al. (1975) noted that the major element abundances of the August 1968 picrite have an affinity with lavas that would eventually erupt from Mauna Ulu between 1969 and 1971. Indeed, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the August 1968 picrite are similar to the June 1969 Mauna Ulu lava (Table 2). Thus, an alternative scenario is that a new mantle-derived magma with a low 87Sr/86Sr ratio (#2a on Fig. 12) bypassed the summit reservoir and mixed with the stored 1960s magma component within the ERZ to create the Aug. 1968 picrite.

Mauna Ulu (1969–1974) and other 1970s ERZ eruptions

The Mauna Ulu eruption created a satellite shield on the UERZ (Fig. 4) from two phases of sustained lava effusion (May 1969 to October 1971 and February 1972 to July 1974) separated by a pause of ∼3·5 months (Swanson et al., 1979; Tilling et al., 1987). Mauna Ulu lavas are mostly olivine controlled (Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980) with relatively high CaO/TiO2 ratios (Fig. 6c) and MgO contents (8·0–11·7 wt % for the six samples analysed in this study). The K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas initially (in June 1969) matched the 1967–1968 summit lavas, whereas most of the subsequent lavas (except for the first sample after the eruptive pause in April 1972, which is intermediate) have lower ratios similar to the easternmost lavas from the August 1971 and July 1974 summit eruptions (Fig. 6b). Similarly, the 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 10b) and 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 12) ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas: (1) decreased from June 1969 to April 1971; (2) increased slightly in April 1972 (after the eruptive pause); and (3) decreased again to relatively constant values in April 1973 and April 1974. The 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the following pairs of Mauna Ulu lavas are distinct at the >95% confidence interval (t-tests #7–9): (1) DAS69-3–2 (June 1969) and DAS71-1213–134 (April 1971); (2) DAS71-1213–134 (April 1971) and MU472-32 (April 1972), from before and after the pause; and (3) MU472-32 (April 1972) and MU474-163 (April 1974).

The isotopic variations of Mauna Ulu lavas are best explained by mixing between three magma components (one stored magma from the 1960s and two new mantle-derived magmas). On a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 13b), the lavas from each phase of the Mauna Ulu (MU) eruption form separate trends (‘early MU’ and ‘late MU’) that intersect between the fields of lavas from the 1961 and 1967–1968 summit eruptions at relatively high 206Pb/204Pb = 18·526 and 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703574 (based on a linear regression of the data from each trend), which is similar to ERZ lavas from the mid- to late-1960s. This intersection point may represent the average composition of the stored 1960s magma component within the ERZ that was preferentially erupted at the beginning of each phase of the Mauna Ulu eruption in 1969 and 1972 (although never in 100% pure form). Conversely, the Mauna Ulu lavas with the lowest 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (in April 1971, and from April 1973 to April 1974) may represent the preferential eruption of two new mantle-derived magmas (one for each eruptive phase) that each progressively flushed the stored 1960s magma out of the ERZ. These magmas (identified below) must be new (rather than older magmas stored within the ERZ) because: (1) they have lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios than older Kīlauea lavas since the early 20th century (Fig. 2); and (2) their combined 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios, which plot on the lower left side of the mid- to late 20th century trend, are distinct from these older Kīlauea lavas (Fig. 7a).

From June 1969 to April 1971, Mauna Ulu lavas trend towards (and beyond) the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the easternmost lavas from the August 1971 summit eruption (Fig. 13b), which were derived from the SC body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Nine analyses of the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703544 ± 5 (±2σm), which is similar to the four analyses of the two easternmost August 1971 summit lavas at the ±2σm level (87Sr/86Sr = 0·703550 ± 1). Thus, the new magma for the early MU trend (#2a in Fig. 13c) may have been contemporaneous magma from the SC body. However, the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these two groups of samples are distinct at the ∼95% confidence interval (t-test #10). In addition, the ∼0.0044 difference in 206Pb/204Pb for these nearly contemporaneous summit (∼18.4918) and rift (18.4874) lavas is greater than the combined ±2σ uncertainty (±0.0016) for each sample. These observations suggest that the new mantle-derived magma for the first phase of the Mauna Ulu eruption (with lower 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas) may have bypassed the summit reservoir on its way to the ERZ, where it mixed with the stored 1960s magma component. The 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava are even more distinct from the (nearly identical) September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas that erupted near Halemaʻumaʻu (t-test #11), which were derived from the HMM magma body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). This larger difference (compared to the broad similarity between the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava and the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas) is consistent with the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the ERZ is connected to the SC body (rather than the HMM body).

From April 1972 to April 1974, Mauna Ulu lavas trend towards the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the easternmost lavas from the July 1974 summit eruption (Fig. 13b), which were derived from the SC body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Thus, the new magma for the late MU trend (#2 b in Fig. 13c) may have been contemporaneous magma from the SC body. In April 1972, however, the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the magma within the SC body would likely have been higher than the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. For example, Pietruszka et al. (2015) attributed the differences in the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the easternmost summit lavas from August 1971 and July 1974 to ∼3 years of progressive magma mixing within the SC body between: (1) a resident magma (equal to the average of the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas); and (2) a single mantle-derived input magma (#2 in Fig. 10a) with a relatively low 206Pb/204Pb ratio. Using this model, the magma within the SC body in April 1972 would have had a 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·4828. If this magma from the SC body (in April 1972) was mixed with the stored 1960s magma component to create the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava (matching its 206Pb/204Pb ratio of 18·4984), the expected 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this hybrid magma would be ∼0·703554 (i.e. almost on the early MU trend). Four analyses of the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0·703563 ± 7 (±2σm), which is (just barely) distinct from the predicted value. If this small distinction is real, the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava might contain a significant component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. It is possible that: (1) this new magma (#2 b in Fig. 13c) with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio than #2a (and a similar 87Sr/86Sr ratio) was delivered to the volcano after August 1971 (most likely during the pause in the Mauna Ulu eruption); and (2) this magma bypassed the summit reservoir to serve as a mixing component in lavas from the late MU trend (prior to fully mixing within the SC body). Thus, the Pb and Sr isotope ratios are consistent with the evidence from: (1) seismicity (Ryan et al., 1981; Ryan, 1988); (2) the major element abundances of Mauna Ulu lavas (Wright & Tilling, 1980); and (3) their two distinct populations of olivine (Vinet & Higgins, 2010) that at least some mantle-derived magma may have bypassed the summit reservoir during both phases of this eruption. This summit bypass might be related to a deep (∼8–11 km) magma body beneath the ERZ (near Mauna Ulu) at the base of the volcanic edifice (Lin et al., 2014).

A third new mantle-derived magma (#2c in Fig. 13c) is required to account for the high 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the high-MgO (and other) 1982 summit lavas (t-test #12). Thus, at least three mantle-derived magmas were likely delivered to the summit reservoir between 1971 and 1982, instead of the one identified by Pietruszka et al. (2015) based only on the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas (#2 on Fig. 10a). In this case, the estimated volume of magma within the SC body during this period (∼0·1–0·3 km3) is probably a maximum. This complication does not affect the suggestion of Pietruszka et al. (2015), based on the spatial and MgO-related differences in 206Pb/204Pb for contemporaneous summit lavas, that the SC and HMM bodies were poorly connected from 1971 to 1982. Indeed, this idea is strengthened by the observation that the 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 12) of: (1) the westernmost summit lavas in August 1971 and July 1974 and (2) the September 1971 and September 1974 summit lavas that erupted near Halemaʻumaʻu, all of which were supplied from the HMM body, are (respectively, for the 1971 and 1974 periods) distinct from the easternmost summit lavas in August 1971 and July 1974 (which were supplied from the SC body). This interpretation is supported at the >95% confidence interval by t-tests #13–16.

Lavas from Mauna Ulu in April 1973 and April 1974, and other contemporaneous eruptions along the UERZ in May 1973, November-December 1973 and July 1974 (Fig. 4), have Pb and Sr isotope ratios that are similar to the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas (Fig. 13b), and thus, the expected isotopic composition of the magma within the SC body (given their eruption dates within ∼1 year of July 1974). The similarity in the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these lavas is supported by ANOVA #2. Conversely, their 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (at the >95% confidence interval based on t-tests #17 and #18) are distinct from both the September 1974 and westernmost July 1974 summit lavas, which were supplied from the HMM body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). These ERZ lavas plot within error of (May and November-December 1973, and 1973 and 1974 Mauna Ulu) or slightly above (July 1974 ERZ) the lower temporal trend in 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 10b). Thus, they may have been derived directly from the SC body at the time of eruption or stored only briefly within the UERZ prior to eruption. Alternately, these ERZ lavas (with the exception of the November-December 1973 lava) may have mixed with a small amount of the stored 1960s magma component because they are displaced to slightly higher 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. The small difference in the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these two groups of samples is significant at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #19). It is also possible that some of the magma that fed the end of the Mauna Ulu eruption (as well as the other UERZ eruptions of 1973 and 1974) continued to bypass the summit reservoir, but this is difficult to discern because the magma within the SC body may have essentially reached the isotopic composition of the input magma by this time (#2 b in Fig. 13c). These observations (like those noted previously for the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava) are consistent with the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the ERZ is connected to the SC body (rather than the HMM body).

Previous studies of the Mauna Ulu eruption have emphasized the importance of a direct mantle control on the major and trace element chemistry of the lavas, including: (1) ten magma batches produced by discrete episodes of partial melting of the mantle (Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980); and (2) a ∼20% relative increase in the degree of partial melting (of a homogeneous source) during the first three years of the eruption (Hofmann et al., 1984). However, the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas suggest that most of these compositional variations are related to magma mixing within the ERZ. The only direct mantle control on the chemistry of Mauna Ulu lavas is recorded by the shift to lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios from the early to late MU trends (Fig. 13b). A total of ∼0·35 km3 of lava erupted at Mauna Ulu, ∼54% from 1969 to 1971 (Swanson et al., 1979) and ∼46% from 1972 to 1974 (Tilling et al., 1987). Assuming a vesicularity of ∼20%, this corresponds to ∼0·3 km3 of vesicle-free magma. If ∼50% of this volume represents the eruption of the stored 1960s magma component, the remainder (∼0·15 km3) may be attributed to the eruption of magma from the SC body and/or the new mantle-derived magmas that bypassed the summit reservoir. This volume is similar to the estimated ∼0·1–0·3 km3 of magma within the SC body from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015), which suggests that magma must have been continuously supplied from the mantle in order to sustain the Mauna Ulu eruption. This interpretation is consistent with the relatively large inflation of the volcano’s summit region from 1969 to 1974 (Wright & Klein, 2014).

ECCENTRIC DECEMBER 1974 ERUPTION AND THE SEISMIC SOUTHWEST RIFT ZONE

The 6-hour December 1974 eruption (Lockwood et al., 1999) was unusual because it occurred along fissures south of Kīlauea’s summit between the KFS and volcanic SWRZ (Fig. 4). Poland et al. (2014) considered this eruption to be the only one from the seismic SWRZ during the volcano’s historical period, whereas Lockwood et al. (1999) associated it with the direct injection of magma from the ERZ into the typically non-eruptive KFS. The eccentric December 1974 lavas are rich in olivine (with minor clinopyroxene and plagioclase) and MgO (12·1–15·7 wt %; Lockwood et al., 1999), which (along with their relatively high CaO/TiO2 ratios; Fig. 6c) is consistent with the accumulation of olivine into a magma (or a mixture of magmas) that had never differentiated significantly beyond olivine control. In addition, the lavas extend to higher 87Sr/86Sr and lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios (combined) than any Kīlauea lavas that erupted earlier in the 20th century (vertical trend in Fig. 13b), signaling the arrival of a new mantle-derived magma (identified below) to the volcano within the ∼5-month period between the end of the Mauna Ulu eruption and December 1974. For example, the high 87Sr/86Sr ratio of the northernmost December 1974 lava is distinct from the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #20).

At least three different magmas are probably required to explain the isotopic variations of the December 1974 lavas. The northernmost December 1974 lava that erupted closest to the caldera has the highest 87Sr/86Sr ratio of 0·703566 ± 8 (±2σm), which is indistinguishable (t-test #21) from the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 13c). The September 1982 lavas display a significant range in 206Pb/204Pb (at constant 87Sr/86Sr) that correlates with their MgO content (Fig. 10b), possibly due to (incomplete) syn-eruptive mixing between a high-MgO magma (206Pb/204Pb = 18·455) from the SC body and a low-MgO magma (206Pb/204Pb = 18·475) from the HMM body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). In December 1974, however: (1) the isotopic composition of magma in the HMM body was probably intermediate between the lavas from the September 1974 and 1975 summit eruptions [206Pb/204Pb = 18·493 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]; and (2) the isotopic composition of the magma in the SC body was probably intermediate between the easternmost July 1974 and the high-MgO September 1982 summit lavas [206Pb/204Pb = 18·464 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. Thus, the northernmost December 1974 lava (with its 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·477) probably does not represent the eruption of contemporaneous magma from either the HMM or SC body alone. A mixture of these magmas with a 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·477 would have a 87Sr/86Sr ratio of ∼0·703558, which is within the ±2σm error of the northernmost December 1974 lava. However, there is no known pathway to mix magma from both the HMM and SC bodies, and transport it to the area beneath the vents of the December 1974 lavas (e.g. Poland et al., 2014). Instead, we propose that a new mantle-derived magma with Pb and Sr isotope ratios similar to the high-MgO September 1982 lavas (#2c in Fig. 13c) bypassed the summit reservoir and directly entered the area beneath the December 1974 vents [i.e. the seismic SWRZ based on Poland et al. (2014) and/or the KFS based on Lockwood et al. (1999)]. This 1982-type magma likely served as one of three mixing components for the December 1974 lavas.

This interpretation is supported (indirectly) by the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr (t-test #22) ratios of the olivine-controlled lava from the November 1979 UERZ eruption (Fig. 13b), which are nearly identical to the northernmost December 1974 lava. By 1979, however, mixing within the SC body between an initial resident magma similar to the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas and the mantle-derived 1982-type magma (#2 in Fig. 10a) was nearly complete [206Pb/204Pb = 18·456 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. In this case, the November 1979 lava probably represents contemporaneous magma (similar to the high-MgO September 1982 summit lavas, but perhaps with a slightly lower 87Sr/86Sr ratio; Fig. 12) from the SC body (∼75%) that entered the ERZ and mixed with a smaller amount (∼25%) of stored magma (Fig. 13c), most likely left over from the Mauna Ulu eruption (itself dominated by the stored 1960s magma component). Thus, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the November 1979 lava (unlike those from December 1974) can be explained by a simple magma mixing scenario that is consistent with the architecture of Kīlauea’s plumbing system (e.g. Poland et al., 2014).

A second mixing component (with relatively high 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr) for the December 1974 lavas (Fig. 13c) can potentially be explained by: (1) contemporaneous magma from the HMM body [206Pb/204Pb = 18·493 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015), corresponding to a 87Sr/86Sr ratio of ∼0·703565]; (2) stored magma from the volcanic SWRZ similar to lavas from the September 1971 eruption; or (3) the stored 1960s magma component. It is impossible to choose between these scenarios based solely on the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of the December 1974 lavas. There are no known pathways to transport magma from either the HMM body or the volcanic SWRZ to the area beneath the vents of the December 1974 lavas, but the seismic SWRZ is thought to be connected to the SC body (e.g. Poland et al., 2014) and a direct injection of magma into the KFS from the ERZ occurred in December 1965 (Lockwood et al., 1999). Thus, it seems most likely that the 1982-type magma bypassed the summit reservoir and mixed with a stored mid- to late-1960s era magma that had previously intruded the KFS (from the ERZ) and/or seismic SWRZ (from the SC body).

The vertical trend of the December 1974 lavas in Fig. 13c requires that this hybrid magma was subsequently mixed with a third magma. This final mixing component (with relatively low 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios) is similar to Mauna Ulu and other UERZ lavas from 1973 and 1974, and the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. Thus, it can potentially be explained by: (1) contemporaneous magma from the SC body [206Pb/204Pb = 18·464 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015), which corresponds to an 87Sr/86Sr ratio of ∼0·703552]; or (2) magma that was only briefly stored (since 1973 or 1974) within the ERZ. The two southernmost December 1974 lavas have the lowest 87Sr/86Sr ratios, and thus, must contain the greatest amount of magma from the SC body (scenario #1) or the ERZ (scenario #2). Scenario #1 would require an intrusion of magma from the SC body to the seismic SWRZ, which is consistent with the model of Poland et al. (2014). However, a direct injection of (briefly) stored magma from the ERZ into the KFS may have occurred in May 1973, when magma migrated westward as a shallow dike from the UERZ into the eastern end of the KFS (Lockwood et al., 1999). This shallow dike likely solidified quickly (Davis, 2015), and it is unknown if a deeper pathway exists to transport magma from the UERZ to the western end of the KFS. Nevertheless, scenario #2 is an intriguing possibility to investigate in the future. If the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the December 1974 eruption tapped the seismic SWRZ is correct, scenario #2 would further require that magma from the UERZ can enter the seismic SWRZ via the KFS.

THE PUʻU ʻŌʻO ERUPTION (1983–2018)

The Puʻu ʻŌʻō MERZ eruption began on January 3, 1983 after a dike intersected stored magma east of Nāpau Crater (Wolfe et al., 1987). The first outbreak of lava was at Nāpau Crater (Fig. 4), but the eruptive fissures extended ∼6 km further down the ERZ. The earliest lavas were differentiated (5·7–6·6 wt % MgO), and most of their compositional variation can be explained by mixing (to create an ‘early hybrid’) between a strongly evolved, rift-stored magma similar (or identical) to differentiated lava from the nearby September 1977 MERZ eruption and a less evolved, rift-stored magma (of unknown parentage) that had also differentiated beyond olivine control (Garcia et al., 1989). The September 1977 lava itself likely fractionated from a 1960s-era summit-derived magma (similar to the stored 1960s magma component) based on its 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 14). The early hybrid magma with a low CaO/TiO2 ratio due to clinopyroxene and plagioclase fractionation (the low-MgO end of the dashed red field in Fig. 6c) was gradually flushed from the ERZ by a contemporaneous summit-derived magma with ∼9–10 wt % MgO and a higher CaO/TiO2 ratio typical of olivine-controlled Kīlauea lavas (Garcia et al., 1992). The summit-derived magma was first detected in Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from March 1983, and its importance as a mixing component grew continuously (based on a temporal increase in CaO/TiO2) until it reached 100% of the erupted lava in February 1985 (ending the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ; Garcia et al., 1992). Modeling of the increase in CaO/TiO2 suggests that this rapid early mixing occurred within a small (∼0.05 km3) magma pocket beneath Puʻu ʻŌʻō (Shamberger & Garcia, 2007).

The 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the earliest Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from January to April 1983 (Greene et al., 2013) are nearly identical to the September 1977 lava (Fig. 14), confirming the interpretation of Garcia et al. (1989). The 87Sr/86Sr ratio of each Puʻu ʻŌʻō sample from Greene et al. (2013) was analysed only once (with a ± 2σ error of ±0·000017, based on their four Menehune analyses). Accordingly, we use average Sr isotope ratios from Greene et al. (2013) for groups of early Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas that erupted over short time intervals (each with a relatively narrow range in 206Pb/204Pb) in the following discussion. For example, the average 87Sr/86Sr ratio of the earliest two Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from January to April 1983 lies within error of the September 1977 lava (t-test #23). Subsequently, the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas decreased rapidly (Fig. 15a), and by September 1984 (when the early period of magma mixing was >95% complete; Garcia et al., 1992), fell below ∼18·455. This critical value marks the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of magma within the SC body in September 1982 (based on the high-MgO September 1982 summit lavas; Pietruszka et al., 2015). It may be used to estimate the amount of magma from the summit reservoir that erupted at Puʻu ʻŌʻō before and after September 1984.

The rate of magma supply during the early years of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption was estimated to be ∼0·11 km3/yr (Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993), or ∼0.2 km3 of magma from January 1983 to September 1984. If ∼50% of this volume represents the eruption of the rift-stored ‘early hybrid’ magma, the remainder (∼0·1 km3) can be attributed to the eruption of 1982-era magma from the SC body. This is similar to the estimated ∼0·1–0·3 km3 of magma within the SC body from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Thus, a substantial amount of 1982-era magma was likely removed from the summit reservoir during the first two years of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption (a period of continuous summit deflation; Thornber, 2003; Wright & Klein, 2014). Our interpretation for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from January 1983 to September 1984 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratios—the rift-stored, 1960s-era ‘early hybrid’ magma was flushed from the ERZ by 1982-era summit magma—agrees with the conclusions of Garcia et al. (1989,1992) and Thornber (2003).

Garcia et al. (1996) first observed a temporal decrease in the MgO-normalized abundances (e.g. CaO or K2O) and ratios (e.g. La/Yb or Ba/Y) of incompatible elements in olivine-controlled Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas over the decade following the end of the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ. These systematic trends continued into the early 2000s (Garcia et al., 2000; Thornber, 2003; Pietruszka et al., 2006; Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013; Thornber et al., 2015). The 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (Fig. 15a) decreased rapidly after September 1984 until they reached a minimum plateau of ∼18·387 ± 2 (±2σ) from August 1988 to October 1990 (Greene et al., 2013). Thereafter, Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas display: (1) short-term fluctuations in 206Pb/204Pb on a time scale of <10 years (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013); and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr to a maximum of ∼0·70364 between ∼2000 and 2003, and a slight decrease thereafter (Fig. 15b). The origin of these compositional variations is controversial.

In their ‘top down’ model, Thornber (2003) and Thornber et al. (2015) argued that the 1982-era summit magma (with, for example, relatively high 206Pb/204Pb, La/Yb, and K2O/TiO2 ratios) was gradually flushed from the summit reservoir (and semi-isolated pockets within the ERZ) by a new mantle-derived magma with low 206Pb/204Pb, La/Yb, and K2O/TiO2 ratios that is represented by Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from ∼2001. This interpretation may explain the two cycles in the K2O/TiO2 ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1996 to 2001 (superimposed on the longer-term decreasing trend) that seem to correlate with the inflation and deflation of the volcano’s summit region (Thornber, 2003). The 2008–2010 tephra glasses from Halemaʻumaʻu and contemporaneous Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas are compositionally (Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015; Fig. 6) and isotopically (Fig. 15) similar. This observation suggests that, as of at least 2008, the remaining 1982-era magma within the summit reservoir had been completely replaced by ‘modern’ Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type magma (Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015). Thornber et al. (2015) emphasize the long-term compositional homogeneity of this Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type magma, and [along with Rowe et al. (2015)] suggest that the 1982-era magma was finally removed from the plumbing system during the surge of mantle-derived magma from 2003 to 2007 (Poland et al., 2012). In summary, the ‘top down’ model accounts for all of the compositional variations of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from mid-1984 to 2007 (beyond the effects of crystal fractionation and accumulation) by two-component mixing between a 1982-era summit magma (stored in the summit reservoir and the ERZ) and a new mantle-derived Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type magma (similar to lavas from ∼2001) that did not vary significantly in composition.

Alternately, we interpreted the chemical and isotopic variations of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (after the end of the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ) to result mostly from a dynamic process of melting small-scale mantle heterogeneities within the Hawaiian plume. This view was characterized as a ‘bottom up’ model by Thornber (2003). Modeling of the temporal decrease in the ratios of incompatible elements and 226Ra-230Th-238U disequilibria from 1985 to 2001 suggests that Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas were increasingly derived from a mantle source that was recently depleted by prior melt extraction within the last ∼8 kyr (Pietruszka et al., 2006). The mantle source region of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas must also contain ancient, small-scale compositional heterogeneities based on the temporal variations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 15). These variations in lava chemistry at Puʻu ʻŌʻō were inferred to result from a single magmatic process—the direct transfer of melt from pores in steady-state equilibrium with the mantle into chemically isolated channels (Pietruszka et al., 2006). When melt is extracted into channels to supply a sustained eruption (such as Pu‘u ‘Ō‘ō), it must be drained from an ever-increasing volume of mantle in order to sustain the flow of melt to the surface. As the eruption continues, the volcano might tap melt from more distal areas and tend to sample: (1) additional melt from recently depleted mantle; and (2) chemically and isotopically distinct melt from ‘fresh’ mantle that never before melted beneath Hawaiʻi.

These rapid, mantle-derived changes in lava chemistry were thought to be efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface because Puʻu ʻŌʻō magma partially bypassed Kīlauea’s summit reservoir, and avoided its buffering effects (Garcia et al., 1996). The evidence for this idea is based on a residence time analysis of the variations in lava chemistry. For example, the rate of change in Ba/Y for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from 1985 to 1992 was a factor of ∼3 faster than observed for summit lavas over the previous 200 years (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). Accordingly, Garcia et al. (1996) suggested that Puʻu ʻŌʻō magma avoided mixing with the magma in the summit reservoir, providing a more direct ‘window’ to the mantle than summit lavas. However, this interpretation relied on the inference that the summit reservoir held ∼2–3 km3 of magma during the late 20th century (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999b), which is now thought to be a factor of ∼10 too large (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Thus, we revisit our previous modeling and interpretations.

We applied the residence time model of Pietruszka et al. (2015) to the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from September 1984 (i.e. after the early period of magma mixing was essentially complete) to October 1990. The model assumes that the temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 15a) results from mixing between: (1) a resident magma with a relatively high initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio (=18·442, based on the September 1984 lava); and (2) a mantle-derived input magma with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio (=18·387, based on the average of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from August 1988 to October 1990). Using the full range in model parameters given by Pietruszka et al. (2015), the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of these Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas are best matched by a residence time of ∼1·6–2·1 years and a magma volume of ∼0·2 km3 (assuming a magma supply rate of ∼0·11 km3/yr; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993), which likely represents the amount of magma that was undergoing mixing within both the summit reservoir and the UERZ to MERZ. Thus, there is no need to call upon a summit bypass for the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption. Instead, the temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb probably results mostly from magma mixing within the summit reservoir, and the nearly constant transfer of this continuously mixed magma from the SC body to Puʻu ʻŌʻō. This interpretation suggests that both summit lavas and lavas from sustained rift eruptions provide a ‘window’ to the mantle beneath Kīlauea, as long as the time scale of the variation in lava chemistry is significantly greater than the typical residence time of magma within the summit reservoir (∼2–3 yr). ‘Top down’ crustal (mixing-related) magmatic processes dominate on shorter times scales (except for rift lavas that bypass the summit reservoir), whereas ‘bottom up’ mantle (source- and melting-related) magmatic processes dominate on longer time scales. All of our previous interpretations of mantle processes at Puʻu ʻŌʻō rely on variations in lava chemistry that span more than ∼2–3 yr.

The critical 206Pb/204Pb ratio of magma within the SC body in September 1982 (∼18·455) may be used to estimate the amount of 1982-era summit magma that erupted at Puʻu ʻŌʻō after September 1984. On a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr, Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from September 1984 to October 1990 are distinct from the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 14) and older Kīlauea lavas since the early 20th century (Fig. 7a). This observation (along with the result of the residence time model) suggests that a new mantle-derived magma with a low 206Pb/204Pb ratio of ∼18·387 was delivered to the summit reservoir before September 1984 (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas first declined below the critical value). Based on the average of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from August 1988 to October 1990, the 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this magma was ∼0·703589. This isotopically distinct melt delivery from the mantle must have occurred after the September 1982 summit eruption (Pietruszka et al., 2015), and it may have coincided with the start of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption in January 1983. It probably did not erupt at Puʻu ʻŌʻō (in ‘pure’ form) until August 1988 (the initial minimum in 206Pb/204Pb) because it first had to flush the rest of the 1982-era summit magma from the plumbing system (via the ERZ). From September 1984 to August 1988, ∼0·4 km3 of magma was supplied to Puʻu ʻŌʻō (assuming a rate of ∼0·11 km3/yr; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993). If ∼50% of this volume represents the new mantle-derived magma, the remainder (∼0·2 km3) can be attributed to the rest of 1982-era summit magma. Thus, the total amount of 1982-era summit magma that erupted at Puʻu ʻŌʻō is inferred to be ∼0·3 km3 (i.e. ∼0·1 km3 before mid-1984 and ∼0·2 km3 from mid-1984 to August 1988). This volume is similar to the estimated ∼0·1–0·3 km3 of magma within the SC body from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015) and the estimated ∼0·2 km3 of magma undergoing mixing within the summit reservoir and the UERZ to MERZ from September 1984 to October 1990.

Our revised interpretation for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from September 1984 to October 1990 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratios—the remaining 1982-era magma was flushed from the summit reservoir (via the ERZ) by a new mantle-derived magma similar to Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas from August 1988 to October 1990—agrees with the conclusions of Thornber (2003) and Thornber et al. (2015). The remaining controversy relates to the: (1) the persistence of 1982-era magma within the plumbing system; and (2) the possibility that the mantle-derived Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type magma entering the summit reservoir has varied in composition. All Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas since 1986 plot on a vertical trend of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr that does not intersect the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 14). This observation is inconsistent with the two-component mixing scenario predicted by the ‘top down’ model. The 1982-era magma (regardless of its storage location) ceased to be a significant mixing component in Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas by August 1988, when the minimum 206Pb/204Pb ratio was reached (Fig. 15a) and the 87Sr/86Sr ratios began to increase (Fig. 15b). Models that call upon the extended residence of 1982-era magma within the summit reservoir, possibly until the 2003–2007 magma surge (Thornber, 2003, Rowe et al., 2015, Thornber et al., 2015), are likely to be incorrect.

The isotopic variations of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (on a time scale of >2–3 yr) after ∼1990 (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013) are interpreted to result mostly from dynamic mantle processes [e.g. the melt extraction model of Pietruszka et al. (2006)]. For example, the <10-yr cycles in the Pb isotope ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas (Fig. 15a) may result from the melting of a fine-scale repeating pattern of filament-shaped compositional heterogeneities (only ∼1–3 km in diameter) in the mantle source region (Greene et al., 2013). Similarly, the vertical trend towards high 87Sr/86Sr ratios for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas can be explained (Fig. 8a) if Kīlauea’s typical pathways of melt extraction migrated slightly towards Mauna Loa, where a mixture of both Kīlauea- and Mauna Loa-like mantle components (as ∼2–4 km wide blobs) might exist (Marske et al., 2008). Our interpretation for Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas since ∼1990 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratios—the composition of melt extracted from Kīlauea’s source region within the Hawaiian plume varied almost continuously, and thus, the related fluctuations in lava chemistry provide a ‘window’ to the mantle—is inconsistent with that idea that the composition of the mantle-derived Puʻu ʻŌʻō-type magma delivered to the summit reservoir remained constant until ∼2007 (Thornber, 2003; Thornber et al., 2015). The apparent correlation between the K2O/TiO2 ratios of Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas and the deformation of the volcano’s summit region (Thornber, 2003) might be related to the delivery of these compositionally distinct magma batches from the mantle.

MODELING OF MAGMA STORAGE TIMES FOR LATE 20TH CENTURY ERUPTIONS

The three mixing trends defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of Kīlauea summit lavas from 1959 to 1982 can be used to infer the pre-eruptive magma storage times of contemporaneous rift lavas. These estimates are based on a comparison between the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of a given rift lava with the model results of Pietruszka et al. (2015) for each of the three summit mixing trends (Fig. 10a): (1) 1959 to 1968; (2) the upper trend from 1971 to 1982 for lavas from the HMM body; and (3) the lower trend from 1971 to 1982 for lavas from the SC body. We determined the time when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of each rift lava (either before, on, or after its eruption date) would lie on each of 20 model permutations of the appropriate mixing trend (see Supplementary DataTable S7 for the individual results). For each model permutation, this time is subtracted from the eruption date (both expressed in years since the start of the mixing trend) to estimate a characteristic time, T. Positive values for T (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the rift lava is higher than the predicted value for contemporaneous summit magma, but similar to the inferred value for older summit magma) reflect the duration of magma storage within the rift zone. Negative values for T (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the rift lava is lower than the predicted value for contemporaneous summit magma, but similar to the inferred value for future summit magma) reflect magma that may have bypassed the summit reservoir on its way to the rift zone.

The uncertainty in T related to the summit mixing trends is difficult to quantify. The 20 model permutations for each of the three summit mixing trends are thought to represent the reasonable extremes of the model parameters that will match the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the summit lavas (Pietruszka et al., 2015), and thus, the greatest potential range in T for a given rift lava. Accordingly, we report the average value for T (±2σ, when appropriate) for each rift lava based on the model permutations (Table 4). In addition, a non-zero value for T was accepted only when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of a given rift lava was different from the predicted 206Pb/204Pb ratio for contemporaneous summit magma by at least ±4σ (±0·0031) based on a majority of the model permutations. Otherwise, the rift lava is assumed to have a storage time of ∼0 yr.

All of the rift lavas from 1961 to 1983 with 206Pb/204Pb > 18.505 (the inferred value for magma within the summit reservoir in 1968), except for the September 1971 SWRZ lava, were modeled with respect to the 1959–1968 summit mixing trend. The Τ values for the 1960s UERZ to MERZ lavas range from ∼0 to 4·1 yr, except for the lavas from August 1963 and December 1965. The August 1963 lava gave Τ=−0·8 ± 0·3 yr and the December 1965 lava gave Τ=−1·0 ± 0·3 yr, suggesting that some magma for these eruptions may have bypassed the summit reservoir. A short magma storage time (or even Τ<0) might be expected for the August 1968 picrite because its relatively low 87Sr/86Sr ratio (compared to other lavas from the 1960s; Fig. 12) suggests that it contains magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. However, the position of the August 1968 picrite on the plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 13b) indicates that it is dominated by 1960s-era summit magma, which is consistent with its Τ=4·1 ± 0·3 yr. A similar observation explains the Τ=4·1 ± 0·3 yr for the June 1969 Mauna Ulu lava, and the longer Τ values (Fig. 14) for the September 1977 MERZ lava (13·9 ± 0·2 yr) and the Puʻu ʻŌʻō lava from January 1983 (19·1 ± 0·3 yr). The September 1971 SWRZ lava was probably supplied directly from the HMM body, so this sample was modeled only with respect to the upper trend from 1971 to 1982. The result is ∼0 yr of magma storage.

The remaining rift lavas were modeled with respect to the lower 1971–1982 summit mixing trend. The Mauna Ulu lavas from May 1970, April 1971, and April 1972 were not modeled because they: (1) have 206Pb/204Pb ratios that plot in the isotopic gap inferred for magma within the summit reservoir in 1968 (18·505) and the SC body in August 1971 (18.492); and/or (2) erupted between 1968 and August 1971 (a period of time that lacked summit eruptions). The November 1979 UERZ lava plots close to the upper trend from 1971 to 1982 (Fig. 10b), and could have been derived from contemporaneous magma within the HMM body (i.e. a storage time of ∼0 yr). However, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the November 1979 lava suggest that it was probably derived by mixing of contemporaneous magma from the SC body (∼75%) and rift-stored magma leftover from the Mauna Ulu eruption (∼25%). Thus, this sample was modeled with respect to the lower trend from 1971 to 1982, and the Τ=7·0 ± 0·3 yr is consistent with this interpretation. The short magma storage times for the eccentric December 1974 lavas (Τ=1·2–2·1 yr) likely result from a balance between the three mixing components identified from their 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios: (1) an older magma stored within the KFS or seismic SWRZ since the 1960s; (2) contemporaneous magma from the SC body or a magma that was only briefly stored (since 1973 or earlier in 1974) within the KFS or seismic SWRZ; and (3) a new mantle-derived 1982-type magma (#2c in Fig. 13c) that bypassed the summit reservoir (with assumed Τ<0). Finally, the short Τ values of ∼0–1·6 yr for the other lavas from the UERZ to MERZ in the 1970s (including those from the Mauna Ulu eruption in 1973 and 1974) are consistent with the idea (based on their 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios) that they were: (1) derived from the SC body at the time of eruption; or (2) stored briefly within the UERZ prior to eruption (possibly mixing, in some cases, with a small amount of the stored 1960s magma component or incorporating magma that bypassed the summit reservoir).

The UERZ lavas were probably stored for the shortest periods of time prior to eruption, ranging from ∼0 to 7·0 yr based on the model results (Fig. 16a). Most of the historical lavas erupted along the UERZ are olivine controlled, and lavas with ≤ 6·5 wt % MgO are absent (Fig. 16b). Lavas with ≤ 6·5 wt % MgO (September 1977 and Puʻu ʻŌʻō in January 1983, January 1997, and March 2011; Garcia et al., 2000; Thornber et al., 2003, 2015) and olivine-controlled lavas (with >7 wt % MgO) are both common along the MERZ. The magma storage times for the MERZ lavas (∼0–19·1 yr based on the model results) range to higher values than the UERZ lavas (Fig. 16a). The longest durations of magma storage beneath the MERZ are for the two most differentiated lavas (Fig. 16c) from September 1977 (∼13·9 yr) and January 1983 (∼19·1 yr). Rift-stored magma, probably from the 1960s, was also inferred to be an important mixing component in the differentiated lavas that erupted uprift of Puʻu ʻŌʻō (within and/or near Nāpau Crater) in January 1997 and March 2011, based on their major and trace element abundances (Garcia et al., 2000; Thornber et al., 2003, 2015). The only estimate for the duration of magma storage in the LERZ (a minimum residence time of ∼550 years) is based on the 226Ra–230Th disequilibria of plagioclase crystals from the strongly differentiated lavas of the early part of the 1955 eruption (Cooper et al., 2001). Thus, there is a spatial increase in the maximum duration of magma storage at Kīlauea from the UERZ (<7 years) to the MERZ (<19 years) to the LERZ (∼550 years for one eruption). The UERZ, based on its proximity to the primary conduit and summit reservoir (Fig. 3), probably experiences a higher long-term average rate of magma supply than the rest of the ERZ (at least, prior to the start of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption in 1983 and the new LERZ eruption in 2018).

Lavas from several eruptions along the UERZ in the 1960s and 1970s (especially August 1968 and 1969–1974 Mauna Ulu) and the seismic SWRZ or KFS in December 1974 may each have at least one component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. Notably, the lavas from each of these three eruptions are relatively mafic [∼8·0–14·2 wt % MgO in this study and Garcia et al. (2003)] and rich in olivine (Lockwood et al., 1999; Garcia et al., 2003; Vinet & Higgins, 2010). There is no evidence that any magma bypassed the summit reservoir and directly entered either the MERZ or volcanic SWRZ.

SYNTHESIS

The magmatic evolution and architecture of the rift zones of Kīlauea Volcano since the mid-20th century is summarized using: (1) the magmatic processes and mixing components (Fig. 11) based on the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of the lavas; and (2) the magma storage times (Table 4). Our interpretations are illustrated using a time series of schematic cross sections through the summit and rift zones of the volcano (Fig. 17). For simplicity, these cross sections depict magma within the rift zones as single dikes.

Fig. 17.
Open in new tabDownload slide

The magmatic evolution and architecture of the summit and rift zones of Kīlauea Volcano from 1959 to early 2018, illustrated using a time series of schematic cross sections.

A magma batch from the mantle (input magma #1 in Fig. 17a) was delivered to Kīlauea’s summit reservoir just before, during, or shortly after the 1959 Kīlauea Iki eruption. The resident magma within the summit reservoir (initially similar to the 1959 summit lavas) progressively mixed with this input magma until 1968. The HMM and SC bodies were well connected at this time. A series of intrusions from the summit reservoir to the ERZ in the 1960s (often leading to eruptions along the UERZ and MERZ) left one or more relatively large pockets of magma (Fig. 17b) to serve as a prominent mixing component in subsequent rift lavas (up to, and including, the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption). This 1960s-era magma, represented by the stored 1960s magma component in Fig. 13, also intruded the seismic SWRZ. The 1960s rift lavas (except the August 1968 picrite) were stored in the ERZ for short periods of time prior to eruption (∼0 to 3·8 yr). The August 1968 magma was stored for several years prior to mixing with a new mantle-derived magma (input magma #2a in Fig. 17b) that bypassed the summit reservoir.

Between 1968 and 1971, this magma batch (input magma #2a in Fig. 17c) began to enter the SC body, which became partially disconnected from the HMM body. This separation may have been related to the initiation of the Mauna Ulu eruption in 1969. Another new magma batch from the mantle (input magma #2b in Fig. 17d) was delivered to the volcano between 1971 and 1972, most likely ending the pause in the Mauna Ulu eruption. Mauna Ulu lavas from 1969 to 1971 (early MU) and 1972 to 1974 (late MU) record progressive mixing (in the ERZ) between each of these magma batches (#2a and #2b, respectively, for each eruptive phase) and the stored 1960s magma component. The two new magma batches for the Mauna Ulu eruption may have been transported to the ERZ via the SC body and/or they may have bypassed the summit reservoir.

Mauna Ulu lavas from 1971, 1973, and 1974, and lavas from other ERZ eruptions in May 1973, November-December 1973 and July 1974, are similar to contemporaneous summit lavas from the SC body. In contrast, lava from the September 1971 eruption on the volcanic SWRZ is nearly identical to contemporaneous summit lavas erupted near Halemaʻumaʻu, suggesting that it tapped the HMM body immediately before or during the eruption. Thus, the ERZ is connected to the SC body (Fig. 17d) and the volcanic SWRZ is connected to the HMM body (Fig. 17c). The duration of magma storage within the ERZ for Mauna Ulu lavas from 1973 and 1974, and lavas from May 1973, November-December 1973, and July 1974 was short (∼0–1·6 yr). Lavas from the eccentric December 1974 eruption, supplied by a mixed magma that was stored within the seismic SWRZ and/or the KFS for a few years, contain a component of new mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir (input magma #2c in Fig. 17d). This magma batch was also delivered to the summit reservoir, where it progressively mixed with the resident magma until (at least) September 1982. The November 1979 ERZ lava is a mixture of this magma from the SC body (after it had nearly reached the composition of input magma #2c) and a mixed, rift-stored magma (Fig. 17e) that was left over from the Mauna Ulu eruption (itself dominated by the stored 1960s magma component).

In 1983, the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption initially tapped a strongly evolved, rift-stored magma similar (or identical) to differentiated lava from the nearby September 1977 ERZ eruption. The September 1977 lava itself likely fractionated from an older magma that was derived from the summit reservoir in the mid- to late-1960s (Fig. 17e). The early Puʻu ʻŌʻō magma was rapidly flushed from the ERZ by 1982-era magma from the SC body. This 1982-era summit-derived magma was itself flushed from the plumbing system by a new mantle-derived magma that was delivered to the summit reservoir between 1982 and 1984 (most likely coinciding with the start of the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption). This magma batch finally erupted in ‘pure’ form at Puʻu ʻŌʻō from ∼1988 to 1990. Thereafter, the composition of melt extracted from Kīlauea’s source region within the Hawaiian plume has varied almost continuously. These mantle-derived changes in lava chemistry were efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface (via the SC body) because the parental magmas for the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption were poorly buffered by the small volume (∼0.2 km3) of magma within the summit reservoir and UERZ to MERZ (Fig. 17f). The similarity of the 2008–2010 tephra glasses from Halemaʻumaʻu and contemporaneous Puʻu ʻŌʻō lavas indicate that the HMM and SC bodies were (again) well connected at this time (and probably until at least April 2018). The current state of Kīlauea’s magmatic plumbing system is unknown.

BROADER IMPLICATIONS

The chemical and isotopic signatures of basalts from mid-ocean ridge and ocean-island volcanoes are frequently used to reconstruct the origin and length scale of mantle heterogeneity, and the process of basaltic melt generation and transport. Many studies have demonstrated that melt or magma mixing—starting with the inception of melting in the mantle and ending with the amalgamation of magma batches in crustal reservoirs (with simultaneous crystallization, and possibly, assimilation)—modifies the primary compositional signals from the mantle (e.g. Reiners, 2002; Maclennan, 2008; Rubin et al., 2009; Stracke & Bourdon, 2009; Shorttle et al., 2016). In this study, we have deciphered the final stages of the complex and dynamic process of crustal magma mixing for Kīlauea Volcano since 1959. Our detailed analysis of the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of contemporaneous summit and rift lavas on an eruption-by-eruption basis has provided a first-order constraint on the timing and composition of melt deliveries from the mantle (Fig. 11) to Kīlauea’s magmatic plumbing system (Fig. 17).

The residence time of magma within Kīlauea’s summit reservoir (typically ∼2–3 years since the mid-20th century) is similar to or shorter than the time scale for the delivery of these compositionally distinct magma batches (<5–10 yr per batch, but perhaps <1–2 yr, as revealed when magma bypasses the summit reservoir). The duration of magma storage within the SWRZ and the most frequently active portion of the ERZ is typically <4 yr. These residence and storage times are short because the volume of magma within the plumbing system is relatively small (<0·5 km3 for the summit reservoir, and probably much less for the SWRZ and UERZ to MERZ) compared to the typical rate of magma supply (up to ∼0·1–0·2 km3/yr during the Puʻu ʻŌʻō eruption; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993; Poland et al., 2012). These factors indicate that the ‘top down’ crustal process of magma mixing at Kīlauea is insufficient to fully mask the ‘bottom up’ mantle source- and melting-related processes. Targeted studies of Kīlauea lavas, and their olivine-hosted melt inclusions (e.g. Sides et al., 2014), from eruptions that: (1) partially or completely bypass the summit reservoir and/or (2) extend beyond the short ∼2–3 yr (summit) or <4 yr (rift zone) time scales of magma mixing will provide the best opportunity to directly witness the production and mixing of incipient melts within the heterogeneous Hawaiian mantle plume.

One or more deeper summit magma reservoirs, possibly at the base of the volcanic edifice and/or the Pacific oceanic crust, have been suggested to exist (generally) for shield-stage Hawaiian volcanoes, and in particular, Kīlauea (e.g. Wright, 1971; Clague, 1987; Lynn et al., 2017). The short residence time of magma for Kīlauea summit lavas indicates that mantle-derived magma batches are not stored for long periods of time in a large crustal reservoir. Any deeper magma body must have a volume that is similar to or smaller than the summit reservoir (<0·5 km3) in order to efficiently transmit the rapid, mantle-derived compositional fluctuations of Kīlauea lavas from the source to the surface. This inference is consistent with the deficits of short-lived 210Pb (t1/2∼22 yr) relative to 226Ra in young Kīlauea lavas, which imply (via modeling of CO2 degassing) that magma ascends rapidly (on a time scale of only ∼8 years) from mantle depths of ∼30 km (Girard et al., 2017). The sum of these factors—a high rate of melt supply and transport from the mantle, a lack of long-term magma storage in a large, deep crustal reservoir, and short magma residence and storage times in the shallow plumbing system—may account for the observation that contamination by the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the Pacific oceanic crust has not significantly affected the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic composition of Kīlauea lavas.

The behavior for Kīlauea outlined in this study contrasts with Piton de la Fournaise (Réunion Island), a basaltic volcano in the Indian Ocean that is frequently active, and like Kīlauea, has a summit caldera with a large pit crater, and rift zones (e.g. Di Muro et al., 2014; Michon et al., 2015). However, the overall rate of magma supply to Piton de la Fournaise is an order of magnitude lower than Kīlauea, and its rift zones are less well developed (e.g. Peltier et al., 2015). Summit eruptions at Piton de la Fournaise are thought to be supplied (e.g. Famin et al., 2009; Peltier et al., 2009; Prôno et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014) from a multi-tiered reservoir, composed of a deep magma body near the base of the oceanic crust (∼7·5 km deep), in addition to a shallow magma body near sea level (∼2·5 km deep) and a near-surface complex of partially solidified dikes and sills (<1 km deep). Estimates for the volume of magma within the shallow body (based on lava chemistry) range from ∼0·1 to 0·4 km3 (Albarède, 1993; Sigmarsson et al., 2005; Vlastélic et al., 2009), which is remarkably similar to our estimate for Kīlauea’s summit reservoir during the late 20th century. The volume of magma within the deeper part of the plumbing system of Piton de la Fournaise is unknown.

Historical lavas from Piton de la Fournaise display short-term, correlated variations in Sr isotope and incompatible element (e.g. Nd/Sm or Th/Yb) ratios that are thought to result mostly from the sampling of small-scale compositional heterogeneities in the mantle source (i.e. the Réunion plume) without large variations in the degree of partial melting (e.g. Pietruszka et al., 2009). The Pb isotope ratios of these lavas vary systematically (but do not correlate simply with either their Sr isotope or incompatible element ratios) and occasionally show large shifts towards highly unradiogenic Pb isotopic signatures during periods of high magma flux and picrite eruption (e.g. Vlastélic et al., 2007, 2009). These fluctuations in the Pb isotope ratios of lavas from Piton de la Fournaise are thought to result partly from the assimilation of Pb-rich sulfides in the lithosphere that are genetically unrelated to Réunion magmatism (e.g. Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016). In addition, the incompatible element ratios and 230Th–238U disequilibria of some historical lavas from Piton de la Fournaise are anomalous due to the contamination of mantle-derived magmas with small amounts (∼3–6%) of low-degree (<1%) partial melts of young, hydrothermally altered gabbro and wehrlite cumulates within the volcanic edifice. Unlike Kīlauea, crustal contamination is an important process at Piton de la Fournaise (e.g. Vlastélic et al., 2005; Salaün et al., 2010) that complicates our ability to identify and track mantle-derived magma batches through the volcano’s plumbing system. The prevalence of crustal contamination at Piton de la Fournaise might be partly related to its relatively low magma supply rate and/or the slow motion of the Indian oceanic lithosphere over the Réunion plume (e.g. Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016). Future studies are required to determine the detailed factors that control the interplay of mantle (source- and melting-related) vs crustal (mixing- and contamination-related) magmatic processes at these and other basaltic volcanoes.
